{"title_page": "Akzidenz-Grotesk", "text_new": "{{Infobox font\n| name = Akzidenz-Grotesk\n| image = AkzidenzGroteskspecAIB1.svg\n| style = [[Sans-serif]]\n| classifications = [[Sans-serif#Grotesque|Grotesque]]\n| date =\n| foundry = [[H. Berthold AG]]<ref name=\"The 1869\u20131978 headquarters of Berthold today\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=The 1869\u20131978 headquarters of Berthold today |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2018/04/the-1869-1978-headquarters-of-berthold-today/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n| releasedate = 1898\n}}\n'''Akzidenz-Grotesk''' is a [[sans-serif]] [[typeface]] family originally released by the [[Berthold Type Foundry]] of [[Berlin]]. ''Akzidenz'' indicates its intended use as a typeface for commercial, or \"occasional\" or \"jobbing\", print runs such as publicity, tickets and forms,<ref name=\"Klim New details\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=New details about the origins of Akzidenz-Grotesk |url=https://klim.co.nz/blog/new-details-about-origins-akzidenz-grotesk/ |publisher=[[Klim Type Foundry]] |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref> as opposed to [[fine press|fine printing]], and \"grotesque\" was a standard name for sans-serif typefaces at the time.\n\nOriginating during the late nineteenth century, Akzidenz-Grotesk belongs to a tradition of general-purpose, unadorned sans-serif types that had become dominant in German printing during the nineteenth century. Relatively little-known for a half-century after its introduction, it achieved iconic status in the [[post-war period]] as the preferred typeface of many [[Switzerland|Swiss]] graphic designers in what became called the [[International Typographic Style|'International' or 'Swiss' design style]] which became popular across the [[Western world]] in the 1950s and 1960s. Its simple, neutral design has also influenced many later typefaces. It has sometimes been sold as '''Standard''' or '''Basic Commercial''' in English-speaking countries.\n==Design characteristics==\n[[Image:Akzidenz-Grotesk variations.svg|thumb|Digital variants of Akzidenz-Grotesk, showing the slight inconsistencies and idiosyncrasies between different weights and widths]]\nLike most [[sans-serif]]s, Akzidenz-Grotesk is 'monoline' in structure, with all strokes of the letter of similar width. This gives a sense of simplicity and an absence of the adornment and [[Swash (typography)|flourishes]] seen in the more decorative sans-serifs of the late nineteenth century influenced by the [[Art Nouveau]] style.{{sfn|Homola|2004|p=29}} Modern type designer [[Martin Majoor]] has described the general design of Akzidenz-Grotesk and its ancestors as similar in letterforms to the [[Didone (typography)|Didone]] serif fonts that were standard printing types in the nineteenth century, such as [[Didot (typeface)|Didot]], [[Walbaum (typeface)|Walbaum]] and their followers.<ref name=\"Majoor My Type Design Philosophy\" /> This is most visible in the quite folded-up [[Counter (typography)|apertures]] of letters such as \u2018a\u2019 and \u2018c\u2019.<ref name=\"Majoor My Type Design Philosophy\">{{cite web|last1=Majoor|first1=Martin|author-link=Martin Majoor|title=My Type Design Philosophy|url=http://www.typotheque.com/articles/my_type_design_philosophy|website=Typotheque|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> The capitals of Akzidenz-Grotesk are wide and relatively uniform in width.<ref name=\"A Neo-Grotesque Heritage\" />\n\nThe 'g' of Akzidenz-Grotesk is a 'single-storey' design, like in many other [[Germany|German]] sans-serifs, but unlike the double-storey 'g' found in most serif faces and in many of the earliest sans-serifs that had a lower-case; sans-serif types first appeared in London, but became popular in Germany from the mid-nineteenth century onwards.<ref name=\"Handover Monotype\" /><ref name=\"Unborn: sans serif lower case\">{{cite web|last1=Mosley |first1=James |title=Comments on Typophile thread \u2013 \"Unborn: sans serif lower case in the 19th century\" |url=http://www.typophile.com/node/46184 |website=Typophile (archived) |accessdate=15 October 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628041224/http://www.typophile.com/node/46184|author-link=James Mosley|archivedate=28 June 2014 }}</ref> [[Walter Tracy]] describes this style of 'g' as a common feature in German sans-serifs of the period and apparently influenced by the tradition of [[blackletter]], still [[Antiqua-Fraktur dispute|very popular]] for printing extended texts in Germany in the late nineteenth century, which uses a single-storey 'g' in upright composition.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=58}}\n\nAs is normal in typefaces cut during the metal type period, Akzidenz-Grotesk shows variation between sizes of metal type, with adaptation of letter-spacing and proportions to different sizes.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" /> In addition, there is variation between weights: [[Karl Gerstner]] notes that even comparing one size (20pt), the medium and bold weights have different [[x-height]], cap height and descender length to the light and regular weights.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" />{{efn|Berthold literature from the 1900s marketed the light and regular weights (light at the time under the name of 'Royal-Grotesk') as being compatible; see below.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe AfB 1904\" />}} This is common with nineteenth-century sans-serifs, which were not designed with the intention of forming an extended family that would match together.<ref name=\"Knockout\">{{cite web|last1=Hoefler|first1=Jonathan|last2=Frere-Jones|first2=Tobias|authorlink1=Jonathan Hoefler|authorlink2=Tobias Frere-Jones|title=Knockout|url=https://www.typography.com/fonts/knockout/design-notes|publisher=[[Hoefler & Co]]|accessdate=21 October 2017|quote=The notion of the \"type family\" is so central to typography that it's easy to forget how recent an invention it is. Throughout most of its history, typography simply evolved the forms that were the most useful and the most interesting, generally with indifference toward how they related to one another. Italic faces existed for decades before they were considered as companions for romans, just as poster types shouted in a range of emphatic tones before they were reimagined as \"bold\" or \"condensed\" cousins. The notion that a type family should be planned from the outset is a Modernist concoction, and it's one that type designers have lived with for less than a century\u2026For more than a century before Helvetica, the sans serif landscape was dominated by unrelated designs.}}</ref><ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> The differences in proportions between different sizes and weights of Akzidenz-Grotesk has led to a range of contemporary adaptations, reviving or modifying different aspects of the original design, discussed below.\n\n==Early history==\n[[File:Schattierte Grotesk 1896.jpg|thumb|right|The release of Akzidenz-Grotesk was not well-documented in contemporary printing literature. However, it seems to derive from this shadowed sans-serif (\"schattierte Grotesk\") from Bauer & Co. of Stuttgart, reviewed in 1896.<ref name=\"Schriftprobenschau 1896\" />]]  \n[[File:Berthold Sweden advertisement.jpg|thumb|right|A 1905 advertisement for Berthold in a Swedish printing journal, offering Royal-Grotesk, later branded as the light weight of Akzidenz-Grotesk, for sale. The sans-serif type is used in a secondary role underneath a more decorative heading face.<ref name=\"Berthold advertisement Alm\u00e4nna Svenska Boktryckaref\u00f6reningens Meddelanden\">{{cite journal |title=Berthold advertisement |journal=Alm\u00e4nna Svenska Boktryckaref\u00f6reningens Meddelanden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vp0TAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA368|date=1905 |pages=106, 336, 368}}</ref>{{efn|The display face appears to be Berthold's Herold.<ref name=\"Reklameschrift Herold FIU\">{{cite web |title=Reklameschrift Herold |url=https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/20935/herold |website=Fonts in Use |accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref>}}]]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk's design descends from a school of general-purpose sans-serifs cut in the nineteenth century.<ref name=\"Shinn Uniformity\">{{cite journal |last1=Shinn |first1=Nick |authorlink1=Nick Shinn |title=The Face of Uniformity |journal=Graphic Exchange |date=2003 |url=http://shinntype.com/wp-content/uploads/Uniformity.pdf |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> Sans-serifs had become very popular in Germany by the late nineteenth century, which had a large number of small local [[Type foundry|type foundries]] offering different versions.<ref name=\"Distribution of sans serif typefaces across German-speaking foundries in the 19th century\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Distribution of sans serif typefaces across German-speaking foundries in the 19th century |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2018/06/distribution-sans-serif-typefaces-across-german-speaking-foundries-19th-century/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Handover Monotype\" /> Berthold literature from the 1920s dated the design to 1898,<ref name=\"Handbuch der Schriftarten\" /><ref name=\"Handover Monotype\">{{cite journal|last1=Handover|first1=Phyllis Margaret|author-link=P. M. Handover|title=Grotesque Letters|journal=Monotype Newsletter, also printed in Motif as \"Letters without Serifs\"|url=http://up.stewf.com/0o400K3p302U|date=1958}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\" /> when the firm registered two [[design patent]]s on the family.<ref name=\"Godfather Reynolds\">{{cite journal |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=The godfather: retracing the origins of Akzidenz-Grotesk |journal=Footnotes |date=2019 |issue=3 |pages=134\u2013143}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds design patent\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Note on the original design patent for Akzidenz-Grotesk |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/08/note-on-the-original-design-patent-for-akzidenz-grotesk/ |website=TypeOff |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nRecent research by Eckehart Schumacher-Gebler, Indra Kupferschmid and Dan Reynolds has clarified many aspects of Akzidenz-Grotesk's history. The source of Akzidenz-Grotesk appears to be Berthold's 1897 purchase of the Bauer u. Cie Type Foundry of [[Stuttgart]] (not to be confused with the much better-known [[Bauer Type Foundry]] of [[Frankfurt]]); Kupferschmid concludes that the design appears to be related to a shadowed sans-serif ('Schattierte Grotesk') sold by the Bauer Foundry and reviewed in a printing journal in 1896.<ref name=\"Schriftprobenschau 1896\" /> Two design patents on Akzidenz-Grotesk were filed in April 1898, first on the 14th in Stuttgart by Bauer and then on the 28th in Berlin by Berthold, leading Reynolds to conclude that the design was executed in Stuttgart.<ref name=\"Reynolds design patent\" /> Some early adverts that present Akzidenz-Grotesk are co-signed by both brands.<ref name=\"JongPurvis2005\">{{cite book|author1=Cees W. de Jong|author2=Alston W. Purvis|author3=Friedrich Friedl|title=Creative Type: A Sourcebook of Classic and Contemporary Letterforms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mDhXoYIGTFAC&pg=PA331|year=2005|publisher=Inmerc|isbn=978-90-6611-250-6|page=331}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2a timeline\" /><ref>{{cite book |last1=Wanetzky |first1=Harald |title=Typotektur: Architektur und Typografie im 20. Jahrhundert : der Modellfall einer Zusammenf\u00fchrung |date=1995 |quote=Berthold und Bauer werben im Jahre 1899 mit einem aus heutiger Sicht seltsam anmutenden [[Jugendstil]]layout f\u00fcr die 'Accidenz-Grotesk'.}}</ref> Early references to Akzidenz-Grotesk at Berthold often use the alternative spelling 'Accidenz-Grotesk'; Reynolds suggests that the name may have been intended as a [[brand extension]] following on from an \"Accidenz-Gothisch\" blackletter face sold by the Bauer & Co. foundry.<ref name=\"Reynolds name source\">{{cite web|last1=Reynolds|first1=Dan|title=Also, the name Accidenz-Grotesk likely came from Bauer & Co., too. That foundry's founder F.W. Bauer had earlier cut a typeface called Accidenz-Gothisch|url=https://twitter.com/typeoff/status/920211001097801729|website=Twitter|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\">{{cite web|last1=Spiekermann |first1=Erik|author-link1=Erik Spiekermann|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk (Re-)Release Dates (comments on Typophile thread)|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628041224/http://www.typophile.com/node/17643 |website=Typophile (archived) |accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref> In general, Reynolds comments that the style of Schattierte Grotesk and Akzidenz-Grotesk \"seem to me to be more of a synthesis of then-current ideas of sans serif letterform design, rather than copies of any specific products from other firms.\"<ref name=\"Klim New details\" />\n\nThe light weight of Akzidenz-Grotesk was for many years branded separately as 'Royal-Grotesk'. It apparently was cut by Berthold around 1902-3, when it was announced in a trade periodical as \"a new, quite usable typeface\" and advertised as having matching dimensions allowing it to be combined with the regular weight of Akzidenz-Grotesk.<ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\" /><ref name=\"Schriftprobe AfB 1903\">{{cite journal|title=Schriftprobe|journal=Archiv f\u00fcr Buchgewerbe|date=1903|volume=40|page=19|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cDsgAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA19|accessdate=22 December 2017|quote=Eine neue recht verwendbare Schrift hat die Firma H. Berthold Akt.-Ges in Berlin geschaffen, eine in acht Graden geschnittene Royal-Grotesk, die sich zu allen besseren Accidenzen verwenden lassen und infolge ihres scharfen und sauberen Schnitts zur besten Wirkung gelangen wird. Auf eine kleine, vielleicht unbeabsichtigte Unsch\u00f6nheit m\u00f6chten wir doch hinweisen. Diese betrifft das Versal-R, dessen Querstrich zu tief steht, was auff\u00e4llt und st\u00f6rend wirkt, wenn der Buchstabe zwischen B und E steht. Vielleicht ist hier eine Verbesserung noch ang\u00e4ngig. Chronos.}}</ref><ref name=\"Schriftprobe AfB 1904\">{{cite journal|title=Schriftprobe|journal=Archiv f\u00fcr Buchgewerbe|date=1904|volume=41|page=149|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OTwgAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA149|accessdate=22 December 2017|quote=Die Firma H. Berthold, Akt-Ges. in Berlin zeigt in einem h\u00fcbsch angeordneten handlichen Heftchen zwei Garnituren Royal- und Akzidenz-Grotesk, beide sich erg\u00e4nzende Schriften von vornehmer Wirkung, die um so mehr als zeitgem\u00e4\u00df bezeichnet werden k\u00f6nnen, weil anscheinend nun endlich auch in der Druckausstattung der Akzidenzen Wege eingeschlagen werden, die zu einer wesentlichen Vereinfachung des Satzbildes f\u00fchren d\u00fcrften.}}</ref><ref name=\"Handbuch der Schriftarten\" /> Reynolds and Florian Hardwig have documented the Schmalhalbfett weight (semi-bold, or medium, condensed) to be a family sold by many German type-foundries, which probably originated from a New York type foundry.<ref name=\"Reynolds distribution of sans serifs\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Research update: Distribution of sans serifs in German-speaking foundries during the nineteenth century |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/04/research-update-sans-serifs-type-german-speaking-foundries-nineteenth-century/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds Longina\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Longina-Schriften |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/typeoff/33857851718/ |website=Flickr |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Mallet Magic\">{{cite web |last1=Hardwig |first1=Florian |last2=Reynolds |first2=Dan |title=Mallet Magic \u2013 Harry Breuer And His Quintet |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/26800/mallet-magic-harry-breuer-and-his-quintet |website=Fonts in Use |accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[G\u00fcnter Gerhard Lange]], Berthold's post-war artistic director, who was considered effectively the curator of the Akzidenz-Grotesk design, said in a 2003 interview Akzidenz-Grotesk came from the Ferdinand Theinhardt type foundry, and this claim has been widely copied elsewhere.{{sfn|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=24|ps=:\"Royal-Grotesk was my favourite font from the beginning. I used it on my first Berthold business card and my letterhead. It's a delicate, slender piece of engraving and came from the royal punchcutter Ferdinand Theinhardt. His foundry came to Berthold in 1908. People always talk about how this sans-serif typeface is \"anonymous\", but it's now clear that it's Theinhardt's. Royal-Grotesk was made for royal scientific printing. And Theinhardt added to it the normal, semi-bold and bold. For me those four weights of Akzidenz-Grotesk are the best.\"}} This had been established by businessman and [[punchcutting|punchcutter]] Ferdinand Theinhardt, who was otherwise particularly famous for his scholarly endeavours in the field of [[Egyptian hieroglyphs|hieroglyph]] and [[Syriac alphabet|Syriac]] typefaces; he had sold the business in 1885.<ref name=\"Liste der Hieroglyphischen Typen aus der Schriftgie\u00dferei des Herrn F. Theinhardt in Berlin\">{{cite book|title=Liste der Hieroglyphischen Typen aus der Schriftgie\u00dferei des Herrn F. Theinhardt in Berlin|date=1875|publisher=Buchdruckerei der K\u00f6nigl. Akademie der Wissenschaften (G. Vogt)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U5oNAAAAQAAJ|accessdate=21 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Theinhardt Reynolds hieroglyphic\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=The Academy of Sciences of the USSR's hieroglyphs font (1928) |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/02/the-academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussrs-hieroglyphs-font-1928/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Typeoff Theinhardt locations\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Berlin locations of the old Ferd. Theinhardt foundry |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/02/berlin-locations-of-the-old-ferd-theinhardt-foundry/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=27 February 2019}}</ref> Professor Indra Kupferschmid, who has researched the early use of sans-serifs in Germany, however reports that this cannot be correct: \"there must have been an Accidenz-Grotesk at Berthold before the acquisition of Theinhardt\u2019s foundry in 1908\",<ref name=\"Some notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid |first1=Indra |title=Some notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk |url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2012/04/ag/ |website=kupferschrift* |accessdate=19 January 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330041347/http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2012/04/ag/ |archivedate=30 March 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\" /><ref>[http://www.typophile.com/node/4567 Akzidenz Grotesk roots]</ref> and confusion may have occurred with fonts held by Berthold that the Theinhardt foundry licensed.<ref name=\"Some notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk\" /><ref name=\"Stefan George Schrift\">{{cite web|last1=Jan-Pool|first1=Albert|title=Stefan George Schrift|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/albert-jan_pool/12100921625/|website=Flickr|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Klingspor Ferdinand Theinhardt\">{{cite web|title=Ferdinand Theinhardt|url=http://www.klingspor-museum.de/KlingsporKuenstler/Schriftdesigner/Theinhardt/FTheinhardt.pdf|publisher=[[Klingspor Museum]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=Some notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk Part 2|url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2017/10/ag-2/|website=kupferschrift|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Schriftprobenschau 1896\">{{cite journal|title=Schriftprobenschau|journal=Archiv f\u00fcr Buchdruckerkunst und verwandte Gesch\u00e4ftszweige|date=1896|pages=404, 407|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gRcDAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA403|quote=Die Schriftgie\u00dferei Bauer & Co., Stuttgart und D\u00fcsseldorf, ver\u00f6ffentlicht unter den heutigen Schriftproben eine schattierte Grotesk und bietet unseren Lesern mit dieser Schrift ein beliebtes, sehr verwendbares Material, das sich in \u00e4hnlicher, \u00e4lterer Ausf\u00fchrung seit jener einen Platz auf allen guten Akzidenzien erhoben hat.}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2a timeline\" /><ref name=\"Dan Reynolds Twitter\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Origin of Akzidenz-Grotesk's weight now sorted. @kupfers was right. Berthold derived it from an earlier Bauer & Co. display typeface. |url=https://twitter.com/typeoff/status/920203429502504965 |website=Twitter |accessdate=7 October 2018 |quote=Origin of Akzidenz-Grotesk's weight now sorted. @kupfers was right. Berthold derived it from an earlier Bauer & Co. display typeface called Schattierte Grotesk. Berthold bought Bauer & Co. The new Berlin + Stuttgart company made an \"unschattierte\" version, which Berthold began selling in 1898 as Accidenz-Grotesk.}}</ref> Reynolds additionally points out that Theinhardt sold his foundry to Oskar Mammen and Robert and Emil Mosig in 1885, a decade before Akzidenz-Grotesk was released, and there is no evidence that he cut any further fonts for them after this year.<ref name=\"Typeoff Theinhardt locations\" /> As Lange commented, it was claimed in the post-war period that Royal-Grotesk's name referred to it being commissioned by the [[Prussian Academy of Sciences]], but Kupferschmid was not able to find it used in its publications.<ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\" /> \n\n[[File:Cologne WWI Notgeld Banknote 10 Pfg 1918 I.jpg|thumb|left|A German banknote from 1918, using a range of sans-serifs of the period]]\nMany other grotesques in a similar style to Akzidenz-Grotesk were sold in Germany during this period. Around the beginning of the twentieth century, these increasingly began to be branded as larger families of multiple matched styles.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> Its competitors included the very popular [[Venus (typeface)|Venus-Grotesk]] of the Bauer foundry of Frankfurt, very similar to Akzidenz-Grotesk but with high-waisted capitals, and Koralle by [[Schelter & Giesecke Type Foundry|Schelter & Giesecke]], which has a single-storey 'a'.<ref name=\"Shaw2017\">{{cite book|author=Paul Shaw|title=Revival Type: Digital Typefaces Inspired by the Past|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n7e0DgAAQBAJ&pg=PA190|date=April 2017|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-21929-6|pages=190\u2013205}}</ref><ref name=\"Koralle Alphabettes\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|title=Koralle|url=http://www.alphabettes.org/koralle/|website=Alphabettes|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Venus - MyFonts\">{{cite web|title=Venus \u2013 MyFonts|url=https://www.myfonts.com/fonts/ftbauer/venus/alternate_cuts.html|website=[[MyFonts]]|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>{{efn|According to Kupferschmid, Ideal-Grotesk, a separate sans-serif face Berthold sold in the first half of the twentieth century, is a Venus knockoff, possibly made by electrotype copying.<ref name=\"Arial addendum no. 3\" />}} ([[Monotype Grotesque|Monotype Grotesque 215]] also is based on German typefaces of this period.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=98}}) Seeman's 1926 ''Handbuch der Schriftarten'' (''Handbook of Typefaces'', a handbook of all the metal typefaces available in Germany, illustrates the wide range of sans-serif typefaces on sale in Germany by the time of its publication.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=58, 92}}<ref name=\"Handbuch der Schriftarten\">{{cite book|title=Handbuch der Schriftarten|date=1926|pages=181\u2013218|publisher=Seemann|location=Leipzig|url=http://www.klingspor-museum.de/Handbuch-der-Schriftarten.html|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> By around 1911, Berthold had begun to market Akzidenz-Grotesk as a complete family.<ref name=\"Berthold specimen c. 1913\">{{cite web|last1='N1KE'|title=Type Specimen book H. Berthold AG, ca 1913|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/n1ke/albums/72157629429950223|website=Flickr|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\" /><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2a timeline\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=Notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk Part 2a \u2013 Timeline|url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2017/12/ag-timeline/|website=Kupferschrift|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Vogelschau.gif|thumb|The poet [[Stefan George]] commissioned alternate characters for Akzidenz-Grotesk for printing his poetry.]]\nWhile apparently not unpopular, Akzidenz-Grotesk was not among the most intensively-marketed typefaces of the period, and was not even particularly aggressively marketed by Berthold.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /> A 1921 Berthold specimen and company history described it almost apologetically: \"In 1898 Accidenz-Grotesk was created, which has earned a laurel wreath of fame for itself. This old typeface, which these days one would perhaps make in a more modern style, has a peculiar life in its own way which would probably be lost if it were to be altered. All the many imitations of Accidenz-Grotesk have not matched its character.\"<ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\" /> An unusual user of Berthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk in the period soon after its release, however, was the poet [[Stefan George]].<ref name=\"Prophet of doom\">{{cite web |last1=Cartwright |first1=Justin |authorlink1=Justin Cartwright |title=Prophet of doom |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jan/14/featuresreviews.guardianreview11 |website=The Guardian |accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> He commissioned some custom [[Uncial script|uncial-style]] alternate characters to print his poetry.<ref name=\"Burke1998\">{{cite book|author-link=Christopher Burke (design writer)|first=Christopher|last=Burke|title=Paul Renner: The Art of Typography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zfT0Iam0q7AC&pg=PA115|date=December 1998|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=978-1-56898-158-1|pages=115\u20138}}</ref><ref name=\"AurnhammerBraungart2016\">{{cite book|author1=Achim Aurnhammer|author2=Wolfgang Braungart|author3=Stefan Breuer|author4=Ute Oelmann|title=Stefan George und sein Kreis: Ein Handbuch|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OaFlCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA480|date=1 January 2016|publisher=Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG|isbn=978-3-11-045688-2|pages=480\u2013481}}</ref><ref name=\"Gewerblicher Rechtsschutz und Urheberrecht Zeitschrift\">{{cite book |title=Gewerblicher Rechtsschutz und Urheberrecht Zeitschrift |date=1943 |page=45 |quote=Gedruckt wurde seit 1904 in der sogenannten Stefan-George-Schrift, einer Letternschrift, die der Graphiker Melchior Lechter im Jahre 1903 in Anlehnung an die Handschrift Georges aus einer freien Akzidenz-Grotesk-Schrift der Schriftgie\u00dferei Berthold, Berlin, geschaffen hatte. Stefan George ist 1933, Melchior Lechtor 1938 gestorben.}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Mid-twentieth-century use==\n[[File:Geisser Plakat Mohrenball 1969.jpg|thumb|left|A 1969 poster exemplifying the trend of the 1950s and 60s: solid red colour, simplified images and the use of a grotesque face. This design, by Robert Geisser, appears to use Helvetica.]]\n[[File:1959 - Kunsthalle Basel - 4 Bildhauer.jpg|right|thumb|Art exhibition poster by Armin Hofmann, 1959]]\nThe use of Akzidenz-Grotesk and similar \"grotesque\" typefaces dipped from the late 1920s due to the arrival of fashionable new [[Sans-serif#Geometric|\"geometric\" sans-serifs]] such as [[Erbar (typeface)|Erbar]], [[Futura (typeface)|Futura]] and [[Kabel (typeface)|Kabel]], based on the proportions of the circle and square. Berthold released its own family in this style, Berthold-Grotesk.{{efn|Berthold-Grotesk is somewhat less well-known than other German geometrics of the period. A licensed adaptation (changing some characters) by the Amsterdam Type Foundry under the name of [[Nobel (typeface)|Nobel]], however, became a popular standard typeface in Dutch printing.<ref name=\"Dutch Typefounders' Specimens\">{{cite book|last1=Lane|first1=John A.|last2=Lommen|first2=Mathieu|last3=de Zoete|first3=Johan|title=Dutch Typefounders' Specimens|date=1998|publisher=De Graaf|pages=29\u201331|url=https://issuu.com/bijzondere_collecties_uva/docs/1998_dutch_typefounders_specimens|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Middendorp2004\">{{cite book|first=Jan |last=Middendorp|title=Dutch Type|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sR9g5xPPJVQC&pg=PA45|year=2004|publisher=010 Publishers|isbn=978-90-6450-460-0|page=45}}</ref> Some twentieth-century sources used different terminology to distinguish between the traditional \"grotesques/gothics\" and the new faces of the 1920s, such as restricting the term \"sans-serifs\" to the latter group.<ref name=\"The Typography of Press Advertisement\">{{cite book|last1=Day|first1=Kenneth|title=The Typography of Press Advertisement|pages=86\u20138, etc.|date=1956}}</ref> The term \"industrial\" has also been used for the early grotesque sans-serifs like Akzidenz-Grotesk.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=98}}}} \n\nHowever, during this period there was increasing interest in using sans-serifs as capturing the spirit of the time, most famously, [[Jan Tschichold]]'s influential book ''Die Neue Typographie'', which praised the aesthetic qualities of the \"anonymous\" sans-serifs of the nineteenth century{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=96}} and was printed in a sans-serif similar to Berthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk.{{efn|Although similar, according to Kupferschmid the type used in ''Die Neue Typographie'' is not Berthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk.<ref name=\"Live Type Research in Barcelona\">{{cite web |last1=Kupferschmid |first1=Indra |title=Live Type Research in Barcelona |url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2014/09/live-type-research-in-barcelona/ |website=Kupferschrift |accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>}} Its comments would prove influential in later graphic design: \n\n<blockquote>Among all the types that are available, the so-called \"Grotesque\"...is the only one in spiritual accordance with our time. To proclaim sans-serif as the typeface of our time is not a question of being fashionable, it really does express the same tendencies to be seen in our architecture\u2026there is no doubt that the sans-serif types available today are not yet wholly satisfactory as all-purpose faces. The essential characteristics of this type have not been fully worked out: the lower-case letters especially are still too like their \"humanistic\" counterparts. Most of them, in particular the newest designs such as Erbar and Kabel, are inferior to the old anonymous sans-serifs, and have modifications which place them basically in line with the rest of the \"art\" faces. As bread-and-butter faces they are less good than the old sans faces...I find the best face in use today is the so-called ordinary jobbing sanserif, which is quiet and easy to read.<ref name=\"The New Typography\">{{cite book |last1=Tschichold |first1=Jan |authorlink1=Jan Tschichold |editor1-last=McLean |editor1-first=Ruari |editor2-last=Kinross |editor2-first=Robin |editor1-link=Ruari McLean |editor2-link=Robin Kinross |title=The New Typography: a handbook for modern designers |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=0520071476}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the post-war period and particularly in Switzerland a revival in Akzidenz-Grotesk's popularity took hold, in what became known as the \"Swiss International Style\" of graphic design. This style often contrasted Akzidenz-Grotesk with photographic art, and did not use [[all caps]] as much as many older posters.<ref name=\"Eskilson2012\" /> Graphic designers of this style such as Gerstner, [[Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann]] and [[Armin Hofmann]] all used Akzidenz-Grotesk heavily.<ref name=\"Reputations: Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann\">{{cite web |last1=Schwemer-Scheddin |first1=Yvonne |title=Reputations: Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann |url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/reputations-josef-muller-brockmann |website=Eye |accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Raposo Swiss Automobile Club\">{{cite web |last1=Raposo |first1=T\u00e2nia |title=Campaign posters for the Swiss Automobile Club |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/4263/campaign-posters-for-the-swiss-automobile-clu |website=Fonts In Use |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Coles Z\u00fcrich Town Hall\">{{cite web |last1=Coles |first1=Stephen |title=Posters for the Zurich Town Hall |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/1329/posters-for-the-zurich-town-hall |website=Fonts In Use |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" /> Like Tschichold, Gerstner argued that the sans-serifs of the nineteenth-century were more \"matter-of-fact\" than the more \"personal\" recent sans-serifs of the previous decades.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\">{{cite journal|last1=Gerstner|first1=Karl|authorlink1=Karl Gerstner|title=A new basis for the old Akzidenz-Grotesk (English translation)|journal=Der Druckspiegel|date=1963|url=http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/a-new-basis-for-akzidenz-grotesk-english-translation.pdf|accessdate=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015202441/http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/a-new-basis-for-akzidenz-grotesk-english-translation.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-15|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Gerstner German\">{{cite journal|last1=Gerstner|first1=Karl|authorlink1=Karl Gerstner|title=Die alte Akzidenz-Grotesk auf neuer Basis|journal=Der Druckspiegel|date=1963|url=http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/akzidenz-grotesk-auf-neuer-basis-german-original.pdf|accessdate=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015202204/http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/akzidenz-grotesk-auf-neuer-basis-german-original.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Art historian Stephen Eskilson wrote that they \"conveyed the functionalist ethos without appearing too stylised...in the manner of the more geometrically pure types.\"<ref name=\"Eskilson2012\" />\n\n[[File:1959 - Gewerbemuseum Basel - Alte und neue Formen in Japan.jpg|thumb|left| 1959 poster by [[Armin Hofmann]] for Japanese exhibition]]\n[[File:Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann 1957.jpg|thumb|right|Classical music concert poster by [[Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann]], 1957]]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk was popular in this period although other typefaces such as Monotype Grotesque were used also: a problem with use of Akzidenz-Grotesk up to the late 1950s was that it was only available in [[metal type|foundry type]] for handsetting. While this was acceptable for posters, by the 1950s [[hot metal typesetting]] machines had become the main system for printing general-purpose body text, and for this system Akzidenz-Grotesk was unavailable until around 1958,{{efn|Date according to ''Helvetica Forever'' and Ulrich Stiehl shows Linotype sales material saying that it was \"taken over to the Linotype machine\" in 1958, although Eskilson reports 1959 for its release.<ref name=\"Helvetica Forever\">{{cite book|last1=M\u00fcller|first1=Lars|last2=Malsy|first2=Victor|last3=Kupferschmid|first3=Indra|title=Helvetica Forever: Story of a Typeface|date=2009|publisher=Lars M\u00fcller|isbn=978-3037781210}}</ref><ref name=\"Akzidenz-Grotesk auf der Linotype-Zeilengu\u00dfmaschine (German)\">{{cite web|last1=Stiehl|first1=Ulrich|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk auf der Linotype-Zeilengu\u00dfmaschine (German)|url=http://www.sanskritweb.net/fontdocs/lino1958.pdf|website=Sanskritweb (blog)|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref>}} when it was first sold on Linotype and then in 1960 on Intertype systems.<ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\">{{cite journal|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk f\u00fcr Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)|journal=Gebrauchsgrafik|date=1959|page=56|url=http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GG/1959-01-01/edition/null/page/68|publisher=Berthold/Linotype (advert)|quote=Die Akzidenz-Grotesk is sechzig Jahre alt, und doch scheint sie nicht zu veraltern, sondern in ihrer Frische und Lebendigkeit f\u00fcr immer zu verharren. Sie erfreut sich solcher Beliebheit, da\u00df sie nun auf die Setzmaschine kam. Zusammen mit den Handsatz-Garnituren bilden die Linotype-Werkschiftgrade eine sehr stattliche Familie, die der Gestalter und Drucker oft und gern bei seiner Arbeit in Anspruch nehmen wird.}}</ref><ref name=\"The Birth of a Giant\" /> Much printing around this time of body text accordingly used Monotype Grotesque as a lookalike.<ref name=\"Hollis2006 Monotype Grotesque\">{{cite book|author=Richard Hollis|title=Swiss Graphic Design: The Origins and Growth of an International Style, 1920\u20131965|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7XO-LMDo4yQC&pg=PA201|year=2006|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|isbn=978-1-85669-487-2|page=201}}</ref><ref name=\"Lees-Maffei2015\">{{cite book|author=Grace Lees-Maffei|title=Iconic Designs: 50 Stories about 50 Things|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qsPuBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA81|date=8 January 2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-0-85785-353-0|pages=81\u20133}}</ref><ref name=\"Roberts2005\">{{cite book|author=Lucienne Roberts|title=Drip-dry Shirts: The Evolution of the Graphic Designer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x2n7ufDeXf8C&pg=PA27|date=1 November 2005|publisher=AVA Publishing|isbn=978-2-940373-08-6|pages=27\u201329}}</ref><ref name=\"Arial addendum no. 3\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|last2=Kupferschmid|first2=Indra|title=Blue Pencil no. 18\u2014Arial addendum no. 3|url=http://www.paulshawletterdesign.com/2011/10/blue-pencil-no-18%E2%80%94arial-addendum-no-3/|website=Paul Shaw Letter Design (blog)|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> In the United States, Akzidenz-Grotesk was imported by Amsterdam Continental Types under the name 'Standard', and became quite popular. According to [[Paul Shaw (design historian)|Paul Shaw]], \"exactly when Amsterdam Continental began importing Standard is unclear but it appears on several record album covers as early as 1957.\"<ref name=\"Helvetica and the New York City Subway AIGA\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|title=The (Mostly) True Story of Helvetica and the New York City Subway|url=https://www.aiga.org/the-mostly-true-story-of-helvetica-and-the-new-york-city-subway|website=AIGA|quote= Exactly when Amsterdam Continental began importing Standard is unclear but it appears on several record album covers as early as 1957.|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Amsterdam Continental: A Handbook of Types\">{{cite web|last1=Devroye|first1=Luc|title=Amsterdam Continental: A Handbook of Types|url=http://luc.devroye.org/Amsterdam-Continental-AHandbookOfTypes.pdf|website=Type Design Information|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Vintage Fonts: 35 Adverts\">{{cite web|last1=Budrick|first1=Callie|title=Vintage Fonts: 35 Adverts From the Past|url=http://www.printmag.com/typography/vintage-fonts-35-adverts-from-the-past/|website=Print|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1957, three notable competitors of Akzidenz-Grotesk appeared intended to compete with its growing popularity: [[Helvetica]] from the [[Haas Type Foundry|Haas foundry]], with a very high x-height and tight letterspacing, [[Univers]] from [[Deberny & Peignot]], with a large range of weights and widths, and [[Folio (typeface)|Folio]] from Bauer.<ref name=\"The Birth of a Giant\" /> Shaw suggests that Helvetica \"began to muscle out\" Akzidenz-Grotesk in New York from around summer 1965, when Amsterdam Continental's marketing stopped pushing Standard strongly and began to focus on Helvetica instead.<ref name=\"Helvetica and Standard Shaw\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|title=From the Archives no. 15\u2014Helvetica and Standard|url=http://www.paulshawletterdesign.com/2011/03/from-the-archives-no-15%E2%80%94helvetica-and-standard/|website=Paul Shaw Letter Design (blog)|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1960s, Berthold could claim in its type specimens that Akzidenz-Grotesk was:<blockquote>a type series which has proved itself in practice for more than 70 years and has held its ground to the present day against all comers...wherever one sees graphics and advertising of an international standard...starting a revival in Switzerland in recent years, Akzidenz-Grotesk has progressed all over the world and impressed its image in the typography of our time.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\">{{cite book|title=Schriftprobe Nr. 473|date=c. 1966|publisher=H. Berthold/Zweigwerk Stuttgart|url=http://www.sanskritweb.net/fontdocs/|location=Berlin/Stuttgart}}</ref><ref name=\"Probe 429A\">{{cite book|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk von Berthold, Probe 429A (digitisation: Stephen Coles/Thomas Maier)|date=c. 1960|publisher=H. Berthold|location=Stuttgart|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/stewf/sets/72157661987768480|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref></blockquote> \n{{clear}}\n\n==Post-metal releases==\n[[File:Parsons Bl IND td 15.jpg|thumb|Signage on the [[New York City Subway]] in [[Screen printing|screen-printed]] Akzidenz-Grotesk (top) and Helvetica (below)]]\nWith the end of mass use of metal type, Akzidenz-Grotesk has been rereleased and adapted in versions for the new [[phototypesetting]] and digital technologies.<ref name=\"Berthold blog 2012\" />\n\nContemporary versions of Akzidenz-Grotesk descend from a late-1950s project, directed by Lange at Berthold, to enlarge the typeface family.<ref name=\"Berthold blog 2012\" /> This added new styles including AG Extra (1958), AG Extra Bold (1966) and AG Super (1968), AG Super Italic (2001) and Extra Bold italic (2001).<ref name=\"Jong Sans Serif\">{{cite book|last1=de Jong|first1=Cees W.|title=Sans Serif: The Ultimate Sourcebook of Classic and Contemporary Sans Serif Typography|date=2006|publisher=Thames & Hudson|location=London|isbn=9780500513118|page=23}}</ref><ref name=\"Berthold blog 2012\">{{cite web|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk|url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/blog/2010-12-08/akzidenz-grotesk/|website=Berthold Types blog|publisher=Berthold Types|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> \n\nSeparately, Gerstner and other designers at his company GGK Basel launched a project in the 1960s to build Akzidenz-Grotesk into a coherent series, to match the new families appearing in the same style; it was used by Berthold for its Diatype system in the late 60s under the name of \"Gerstner-Programm\" but according to Lange it was never fully released.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" /><ref name=\"FIU Gerstner-Programm\">{{cite web|title=Gerstner-Programm|url=https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/39674/gerstner-programm|website=Fonts in Use|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=26}} A digitisation has been released by the digital type foundry Forgotten Shapes.<ref name=\"Forgotten Shapes Gerstner-Programm\">{{cite web |last1=Raabe |first1=Marcel |title=Gerstner-Programm |url=https://forgotten-shapes.com/gerstner-programm?article=gerstner-programm |publisher=Forgotten Shapes |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe current holder of the Berthold rights is Berthold Types of Chicago, following the bankruptcy of H. Berthold AG of Germany in 1993.<ref name=\"Berthold Goes Bankrupt\">{{cite web|title=Berthold Goes Bankrupt|url=https://www.telecompaper.com/news/berthold-goes-bankrupt--4639|website=Telecompaper|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Harvey Hunt 2004 statement\">{{cite web|last1=Hunt|first1=Harvey|title=Erik Spiekermann's Statements re Berthold|url=http://www.typophile.com/node/5063|website=Typophile|publisher=Berthold Types|accessdate=20 October 2017|date=2004}}</ref> Berthold released Akzidenz-Grotesk in [[OpenType]] format in 2006, under the name Akzidenz-Grotesk Pro, and added matching Cyrillic and Greek characters the next year.<ref>[http://www.creativepro.com/story/news/24218.html Berthold Announces the Release of Akzidenz-Grotesk in OpenType Format] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060518120415/http://www.creativepro.com/story/news/24218.html |date=2006-05-18 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.microsoft.com/typography/links/news.aspx?NID=5786 AG goes Greek and Cyrillic]</ref> \n==Reception==\nAs described above, many influential graphic designers have used Akzidenz-Grotesk. In 2013, [[Pentagram (design firm)|Pentagram]] partner Domenic Lippa rated Akzidenz-Grotesk as \"probably the best typeface ever designed...it doesn\u2019t overdominate when used, allowing the designer more freedom and versatility\".<ref name=\"Lippa 2013\">{{cite web |last1=Lippa |first1=Domenic |title=The 10 best fonts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/gallery/2013/sep/14/the-10-best-fonts |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> [[Kris Sowersby]] has written that he found the semi-bold and bold weights most satisfying.<ref name=\"Sowersby S\u00f6hne design information\" /> Lange commented that the light weight \"was my favourite font from the beginning. I used it on my first Berthold business card and my letterhead. It's a delicate, slender piece of engraving.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=24}}</ref>\n\nA particular criticism of Akzidenz-Grotesk however, has often been that the regular weight has its rather wide capitals that look unbalanced relative to the lower-case, which is problematic in extended text: Adrian Frutiger commented that Akzidenz-Grotesk forms \"patches in print\";{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=96}} Reynolds that in a digital version \"the capital letters are slightly too dark, and slightly too close to the lowercase letters that follow them in a word\"<ref name=\"Review: Graphic Design and the Soul\" /> and Wolfgang Homola that in Helvetica \"the weight of the stems of the capitals and the lower case is better balanced\".{{sfn|Homola|2004|p=33}}\n\n==Distinctive characteristics==\n[[File:Akzidenz-Grotesk comparison.png|thumb|The letterforms of Akzidenz-Grotesk show a \"folded-up\" structure with narrow [[Counter (typography)|apertures]], similar to [[Didone (typography)|Didone]] serif typefaces popular in Europe at the time, such as the work of [[Justus-Erich Walbaum]].{{efn|This image shows a later revival of Walbaum's work; during the early nineteenth century figures in roman type were customarily [[Text figures|of variable height]].}} [[Frutiger (typeface)|Frutiger]], a design intended for maximum legibility, shows a much more open design.{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=250}} Twentieth-century neo-grotesques such as Helvetica intensify the effect by making almost all terminals horizontal or vertical.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" />]]\nCharacteristics of this typeface are:\n\n'''lower case:'''\nA 'folded-up' structure with narrow apertures and strokes curled up towards the vertical, most obvious on letters such as c, e, s and a. Stroke endings are though less consistently horizontal or vertical than in Helvetica. A square dot over the letter i. Double-storey a, single-storey g.\n\n'''upper case:'''\nG with a vertical spur. A dropped horizontal stroke on A. The capitals are wide and have relatively little variation in width, with letters like 'E' and 'F' quite wide.<ref name=\"A Neo-Grotesque Heritage\">{{cite web|last1=Berry|first1=John|title=A Neo-Grotesque Heritage|url=http://acumin.typekit.com/history/|publisher=Adobe Systems|quote=With its horizontal and vertical strokes of almost the same thickness and its regularized capital letters with few variations of width, Akzidenz Grotesk stood out starkly on the page \u2013 especially when that page also included the highly-decorated types that were popular in the same era.|accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=18}} The 'M' is straight-sided with the diagonals meeting in the bottom centre of the letter. Capitals in several weights have very noticeably thicker strokes than the lower-case.{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=61}}<ref name=\"Review: Graphic Design and the Soul\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Review: Graphic Design and the Soul |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2010/11/graphic-design-and-the-soul/ |website=TypeOff |accessdate=17 April 2019 |quote=The capital letters are slightly too dark, and slightly too close to the lowercase letters that follow them in a word.}}</ref> On many but not all styles a straight leg on the 'R' and a 'Q' where the outstroke does not cut through the letter.\n\n'''number:'''\nA top serif on the 1 and in some styles a downward-pointing serif on the top left of the 7.\n\nIt is important to note, however, that as the weights and sizes of Akzidenz-Grotesk were cut separately not all these features will appear on all styles.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /> For instance, the 't' of the Schmalhalbfett weight only has no base, as it was designed separately and not by Berthold.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" />\n\nAkzidenz-Grotesk did not have italics until the post-war period.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> Its slanted form is an [[oblique type|oblique]] rather than a [[italic type|true italic]].<ref name=Majoor>{{cite web|last1=Majoor|first1=Martin|author-link1=Martin Majoor|title=Inclined to be dull|url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/inclined-to-be-dull|website=Eye magazine|accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref> This means that the letters are slanted without using handwriting forms.<ref name=\"Majoor My Type Design Philosophy\" /> During the metal type period, when italics for Akzidenz-Grotesk were not available, Amsterdam Continental marketed those of an unrelated typeface, Mercator, as companions instead.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n==Versions==\n===Metal type versions===\n[[File:Standard (Akzidenz Grotesque) Specimen (4083757282).jpg|thumb|Popular for poster setting, Akzidenz-Grotesk's bold weight has always been one of the best-known members of the family.]]\nBerthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk family by the late metal type period included the following styles. English names are taken from Berthold's Type Specimen (Schriftprobe) No. 473 except where stated otherwise:\n* Akzidenz-Grotesk (Standard, available on Linotype in modified form as series 57 with [[Oblique type|oblique]])<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Helvetica Forever\" />{{efn|An alternative 'R' with curled leg was available by request.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}\n* Halbfett (Medium or literally semi-bold, available on Linotype in modified form as series 58 and as poster type)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Helvetica Forever\" />{{efn|An alternative 'R' with curled leg was available by request.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}\n* Mager (Light, sometimes sold as Royal-Grotesk)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Fett (Bold, available as poster type)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Schmalmager (Light Condensed)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Eng (Condensed)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Schmalhalbfett (Medium Condensed,<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> originally called \"Steinschrift eng\".{{efn|Or Enge Steinschrift}} Not designed by Berthold.<ref name=\"Reynolds typefaces named Royal or Akzidenz\" /><ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\" /> The 'R' has a curled leg and in metal type the 't' no base.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />)\n[[File:Standard Bold Condensed Type Specimen (14411557573).jpg|thumb|Akzidenz-Grotesk had several condensed weights in the metal type period, such as this condensed bold.]]\n* Schmalfett (Bold Condensed,<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /><ref name=\"Reynolds typefaces named Royal or Akzidenz\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=German, Swiss, and Austrian typefaces named Royal or Akzidenz |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/02/typefaces-with-royal-accidenz-or-akzidenz-in-their-names/ |website=TypeOff |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\" /> originally called \"B\u00fccher-Grotesk halbfett\".{{efn|Or Halbfette B\u00fccher-Grotesk}} Available as poster type, 'R' with a curled leg)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Extra (Extrabold Condensed, tighter-spaced than the Schmalfett weight)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />\n* Extrafett (Compact, or literally, also extra-bold)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />{{efn|Ulrich Stiehl suggests that this may have been one of the last additions to the metal type family: it does not appear in a 1959 advert<ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" /> or Berthold's Hauptprobe Nr. 470, but it does in the slightly later Schriftprobe Nr. 473, which he suggests dates from c. 1966.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}\n[[File:Standard (Akzidenz Grotesque) Specimen (4083751496).jpg|thumb|With its four-terminal 'w', Akzidenz-Grotesk Skelett (Extralight Extended) was one of the most divergent and least popular members of the family in the metal type period.<ref name=\"Sowersby S\u00f6hne design information\" />]]\n* Skelett (Extralight Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Breitmager (Light Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Breit (Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />\n* Breithalbfett (Medium Extended, or literally Semi-bold Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />{{efn|A less folded-up 'a' and 'g' and a narrower 'r' were available by request.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}<ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Breitfett (Extrabold Extended, or literally Bold Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />{{efn|A less folded-up 'a' and 'g' and a narrower 'r' were available by request.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}<ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\nReynolds prefers 'Bold Condensed' to describe the Schmalhalbfett and 'Condensed Heavy' for the Schmalfett.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> Other weights were added by the time of the phototypesetting and digital versions, such as the ultra-bold 'Akzidenz-Grotesk Super'.<ref name=\"Jong Sans Serif\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n===Akzidenz-Grotesk Buch===\n[[Image:Akzidenz-Grotesk Book.svg|thumb|Berthold's phototype Akzidenz-Grotesk Buch was heavily based on Helvetica; the two are almost indistinguishable.]]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk Buch (Book) is a variant designed by Lange between 1969 and 1973. Designed after Helvetica had become popular, it incorporates some of its features, such as strike-through tail in 'Q', a curved tail for the 'R', horizontal and vertical cut stroke terminators.<ref name=\"Karow2012\">{{cite book|author=Peter Karow|title=Font Technology: Methods and Tools|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5MeoCAAAQBAJ|date=6 December 2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-642-78505-4|pages=225-8, 235-40}}</ref> As in some Helvetica versions, the [[cedilla]] is replaced with a comma.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schwartz|first1=Christian|title=Neue Haas Grotesk|url=http://www.christianschwartz.com/haasgrotesk.shtml|accessdate=28 November 2014}}</ref> Former Berthold font designer [[Erik Spiekermann]] has called Lange's \"answer to Helvetica.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Spiekermann|first1=Eric|authorlink1=Erik Spiekermann|title=Twitter post|url=https://twitter.com/espiekermann/status/580497573800255488|website=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=21 July 2016|quote=AG Buch war [[Gunter Gerhard Lange|GGL's]] Antwort auf Helvetica, f\u00fcr die Berthold keine Lizenz kriegte von Linotype.}}</ref> Late in life Lange made no apology for it, commenting when asked about a design alleged to be a copy of one of his own original designs: \"there are also people who say that the best Helvetica is my AG Book.\"{{sfn|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=23}}\n\nDigital versions included Greek and Cyrillic characters, and the family includes a condensed, extended, rounded and stencil series.<ref name=\"AG Book Pro\">{{cite web|title=AG Book Pro|url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book/proplus/|publisher=Berthold|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"AG Book Rounded Pro website\">{{cite web|title=AG Book Rounded Pro|url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book-rounded/proplus/|publisher=Berthold|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n===Akzidenz-Grotesk Schulbuch===\n[[File:Akzidenz Grotesk Schulbuch.png|thumb|Akzidenz-Grotesk Schulbuch, showing its unusual capital 'i']]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk Schulbuch (Schoolbook) of 1983 is a variant of Akzidenz-Grotesk Buch which was also designed by Lange.<ref name=\"Schoolbook Pro\">{{cite web |title=AG Schoolbook\u00ae Pro |url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-schoolbook/pro/ |publisher=Berthold Types |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> It uses [[schoolbook characters]], characters intended to be more distinct and closer to handwritten forms to be easier for children to recognise.<ref name=\"Walter Reynolds 2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Walker |first1=Sue |last2=Reynolds |first2=Linda |title=Serifs, sans serifs and infant characters in children\u2019s reading books |journal=Information Design Journal |date=1 January 2003 |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages=106\u2013122 |doi=10.1075/idj.11.2.04wal}}</ref>\n\nGenerally based on Akzidenz-Grotesk Book, it includes a single-storey 'a', curled 'l', lower- and upper-case 'k' that are symmetrical, and 't', 'u' and 'y' without curls on the base. The 'J' has a top bar, the 'M' centre does not descend to the baseline and the 'G' and 'R' are simplified in the manner of Futura. A particularly striking feature is a blackletter-style default upper-case 'i' with a curl at the bottom: this is rarely encountered in the English-speaking world (it would more commonly be recognized as a J), but much more common in Germany.<ref name=\"Wikipedia Redefined\">{{cite web|last1=Coles|first1=Stephen|title=Wikipedia Redefined|url=http://fontsinuse.com/uses/2013/wikipedia-redefined|website=Fonts in Use|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Design Museum FIU\">{{cite web|last1=Coles|first1=Stephen|title=Design Museum|url=http://fontsinuse.com/uses/11997/design-museum-identity-2003-2016|website=Fonts in Use|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nEach weight is available in two fonts featuring alternative designs. In 2008, OpenType Pro versions of the fonts were released. [[FontFont]]'s FF Schulbuch family is in a similar style.<ref name=\"Design Museum FIU\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n===Akzidenz-Grotesk Old Face===\n[[File:Akzidenz Grotesk Old Face.png|thumb|Sample image of Akzidenz-Grotesk Old Face, a [[phototypesetting]] version of Akzidenz-Grotesk intended to incorporate more of the original inconsistencies and different x-heights of the metal type]]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk Old Face, designed by Lange and released in 1984, was intended to be more true to the metal type than previous phototypesetting versions and incorporate more of the original type's inconsistencies of dimensions such as x-height.<ref name=\"AG Old Face Pro website\">{{cite web|title=AG Old Face Pro|url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-old-face/pro/|publisher=Berthold Types|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=26}} It also incorporates a comma-style cedilla in the medium and bold weights, inward hook in regular-weighted [[\u00df]], and a shortened horizontal serif on the regular-weighted ''1''.<ref name=\"AG Old Face weights\" />\n\nRegular, medium, bold, outline, bold outline and shaded styles were made for the family, but no obliques.<ref name=\"AG Old Face weights\">{{cite book|title=Berthold exklusiv Probe 013: Akzidenz-Grotesk|date=1984|publisher=Berthold Fototype|location=Berlin|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/101656904@N05/33820314480/in/album-72157679746685343/|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"AG Old Face Pro website\" />\n\n===Akzidenz-Grotesk Next===\nIn December 2006, Berthold announced the release of Akzidenz-Grotesk Next.<ref>[http://www.microsoft.com/typography/links/news.aspx?NID=5711 Berthold Releases Akzidenz-Grotesk Next]</ref> Designed by Bernd M\u00f6llenst\u00e4dt and Dieter Hofrichter, this typeface family features readjusted x-heights and weights throughout the family, giving a more consistent design. The family consists of 14 variants with 7 weights in roman and italic, in a single width.\n{{clear}}\n==Similarities to other typefaces==\n[[Image:AGcomparison08.svg|thumb|Comparison of distinguishing characters in Akzidenz-Grotesk, [[Folio (typeface)|Folio]], [[Helvetica]], and [[Univers|Univers 55]]]]\n[[Image:Akzindenz-helvetica-xheight.svg|thumb|The regular weight of Akzidenz-Grotesk had a lower x-height than [[Helvetica]]]]\nSeveral type designers modelled typefaces on this popular typeface in the 1950s; Reynolds comments that the original Akzidenz-Grotesk has limitations in extended text: \"the capital letters are slightly too dark.\"<ref name=\"Review: Graphic Design and the Soul\" /> [[Max Miedinger]] at the Haas Foundry used it as a model for the typeface Neue Haas-Grotesk, released in 1957 and renamed Helvetica in 1961. Miedinger sought to refine the typeface making it more even and unified, with a higher x-height, tighter spacing and generally horizontal terminals.<ref name=\"The Birth of a Giant\" /> Two other releases from 1957, Adrian Frutiger's Univers and Bauer's Folio, take inspiration from Akzidenz-Grotesk; Frutiger's goal was to eliminate what he saw as unnecessary details, removing the dropped spur at bottom right of the G and converting the '1' and the '7' into two straight lines.<ref name=\"Gehlhaar\">{{cite web |last1=Gehlhaar |first1=Jens |title=Neuwelt: an optimistic transatlantic sans serif type family |url=https://jensgehlhaar.com/Neuwelt-An-optimistic-transatlantic-sans-serif-type-family |website=Jens Gehlhaar |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=97|ps=: \"The curved indent in the upstroke of the 1, like in Akzidenz Grotesk, was something alien to me. An upstroke is something simple and not so fanciful, horizontal with a bump in it. Accordingly, my 1 is simple, like the 7 is too.\"}}\n\nMuch more loosely, [[Transport (typeface)|Transport]], the typeface used on British road signs, was designed by [[Jock Kinneir]] and [[Margaret Calvert]] influenced by Akzidenz-Grotesk.<ref name=\"New Transport\">{{cite web|title=New Transport|first=Margaret|last=Calvert|author-link=Margaret Calvert|url=http://www.newtransport.co.uk/|publisher=A2-Type|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> However, many adaptations and letters influenced by other typefaces were incorporated to increase legibility and make characters more distinct.<ref name=\"From Akzidenz to Transport Solution\">{{cite web|last1=Sudjic|first1=Deyan|title=From Akzidenz to Transport Solution|url=http://www.port-magazine.com/design/from-akzidenz-to-transport-solution/|website=Port|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Jackson2013\">{{cite book|first=Tanya|last=Jackson|title=British Railways: The Nation's Railway|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jcc7AwAAQBAJ&pg=PT130|date=31 January 2013|publisher=History Press|isbn=978-0-7524-9742-6|page=130}}</ref>\n\n===\"Akzidenz-Grotesk\" (Haas)===\n{{main|Normal-Grotesk}}\nA completely different \"Akzidenz-Grotesk\" was made by the [[Haas Type Foundry]] of Switzerland. Also named \"Accidenz-Grotesk\" and \"Normal-Grotesk\", it had a more condensed, \"boxy\" design.<ref name=\"Eskilson2012\">{{cite book|first=Stephen|last=Eskilson|title=Graphic Design: A New History, Second Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WUEv45FsrmsC&pg=PA290|date=28 February 2012|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-17260-7|pages=290\u20131}}</ref><ref name=\"The Birth of a Giant\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=The Birth of a Giant|url=http://www.fontbureau.com/nhg/history/|publisher=[[Font Bureau]]|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref> Kupferschmid describes it as a \"reworking of \"Neue Moderne Grotesk\", originally ca. 1909 by Wagner & Schmidt, Leipzig. Initially issued by Haas under the name \"Accidenz-Grotesk\", later spelled \"Akzidenz-Grotesk\" but 1943 revised and renamed \"Normal-Grotesk\" to prevent confusion with Berthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk.\"<ref name=\"Haas Normal-Grotesk Flickr\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=Haas Normal-Grotesk|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/kupfers/6198185700|website=Flickr|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Wagner & Schmidt, etc.\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=Wagner & Schmidt, etc.|url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2016/10/wagner-schmidt-etc/|website=kupferschrift|accessdate=18 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119053731/http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2016/10/wagner-schmidt-etc/|archive-date=19 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Haas Foundry created Helvetica in response to its decline in popularity in competition with Berthold's design.<ref name=\"Eskilson2012\"/>\n\n===Alternative digitisations===\nAs typeface designs are generally not legally protected (unlike their names, which can be trademarked),<ref name=\"AG Next Trademark\">{{cite web |title=AKZIDENZ-GROTESK NEXT \u2013 Trademark Details |url=https://trademarks.justia.com/872/09/akzidenz-grotesk-87209238.html |publisher=Just |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> several alternative digitisations inspired by Akzidenz-Grotesk have been released under alternative names. The Swiss digital type foundry Optimo has released an alternative digitisation of Akzidenz-Grotesk named \"Theinhardt\".<ref name=\"Theinhardt Grotesk\">{{cite web|title=Theinhardt|url=http://optimo.ch/typefaces_Theinhardt_all_Specimen.html|publisher=Optimo|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> Spiekermann has praised this as \"the best\" Akzidenz-Grotesk digitisation.<ref name=\"Thienhardt Spiekermann\">{{cite web|last1=Spiekermann|first1=Erik|authorlink1=Erik Spiekermann|title=Twitter post|url=https://twitter.com/espiekermann/status/580502828122284032|website=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=21 July 2016|quote=ist ja auch die beste AG}}</ref> [[Mergenthaler Linotype Company|Linotype]], which started to sell Akzidenz-Grotesk on its hot metal typesetting system in the 1950s, continues to sell a limited digital version under the other common alternative name, 'Basic Commercial', and [[Bitstream Inc.|Bitstream]] offer a two-weight version named 'Gothic 725'.<ref name=\"Basic Commercial LT\">{{cite web|title=Basic Commercial LT|url=https://www.myfonts.com/fonts/linotype/basic-commercial-lt/|website=MyFonts|publisher=Linotype|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Gothic 725\">{{cite web|title=Gothic 725|url=https://www.myfonts.com/fonts/bitstream/gothic-725/|website=[[MyFonts]]|publisher=[[Bitstream Inc.]]|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> A proprietary digitisation named NYC Sans, by Nick Sherman and Jeremy Mickel, is the corporate font of New York City's tourist board [[NYC & Company]].<ref name=\"NYC Sans Hex\">{{cite web |title=NYC Sans |url=https://hex.xyz |publisher=Hex Projects |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NYC SANS - Trademark Details\">{{cite web |title=NYC SANS \u2013 Trademark Details |url=https://trademarks.justia.com/865/03/nyc-86503390.html |publisher=[[Justia]] |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NYC Gets A Major Rebrand FastCo\">{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Meg |title=NYC Gets A Major Rebrand (And Its First Official Pictograms) |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3060794/nyc-gets-a-major-rebrand-and-its-first-official-pictograms |website=Fast Company |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Lessard NYC Go rebrand details\">{{cite web |last1=Lessard |first1=Emily |title=NYC Go rebrand details |url=http://emilylessard.com/nycgo-typography/ |publisher=Emily Lessard |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> Transport has also been digitised in several versions.<ref name=\"Transport URW\">{{cite web|title=Transport|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/urw/transport/|website=MyFonts|publisher=URW++|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"New Transport\" /> The American publisher CastleType has released a digitisation originally created for ''[[San Francisco Focus]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"Standard CT\">{{cite web |last1=Castle |first1=Jason |title=Standard CT |url=https://www.myfonts.com/fonts/castletype/standard/ |website=[[MyFonts]] |publisher=CastleType |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> Spiekermann has also released with Ralph du Carrois a very loose digitisation of Akzidenz Grotesk, FF Real, in two [[optical size]]s, with variant features like a two-storey 'g', [[Typographic ligature|ligatures]], and a true italic.<ref name=\"FF Real LT\">{{cite web|title=FF Real|url=https://www.linotype.com/8050/ff-real.html|website=Linotype|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Interview with Erik Spiekermann and Ralph du Carrois\">{{cite web|last=Ulrich|first=Ferdinand|title=Interview with Erik Spiekermann and Ralph du Carrois|url=https://www.fontshop.com/content/interview-with-erik-spiekermann-and-ralph-olivier-du-carrois-1|website=FontShop|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> A digitisation named S\u00f6hne, in three widths with [[Monospaced typeface|a monospaced version]] was released by Kris Sowersby in 2019.<ref name=\"Sowersby S\u00f6hne design information\">{{cite web |last1=Sowersby |first1=Kris |title=S\u00f6hne design information |url=https://klim.co.nz/blog/soehne-design-information/ |publisher=[[Klim Type Foundry]] |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Klim New details\" /><ref name=\"Stinson S\u00f6hne\">{{cite web |last1=Stinson |first1=Liz |title=A Modern Sans-serif Infused With the Spirit of the NYC Subway |url=https://eyeondesign.aiga.org/a-modern-sans-serif-infused-with-the-spirit-of-the-nyc-subway/ |website=AIGA Eye On Design |publisher=[[AIGA]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> A digitisation of Stefan George-Schrift by Colin Kahn has been published by [[P22 (type foundry)|P22]].<ref name=\"P22 St G Schrift\">{{cite web |title=St G Schrift |url=https://p22.com/family-St_G_Schrift |publisher=[[P22 (type foundry)|P22]] |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notable users==\n<!-- **ALL** uses need a reference -->\n[[File:Gestaltungsprobleme cover comparison.jpg|thumb|The cover of Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann's 1961 book ''The Graphic Artist and His Design Problems'' used Akzidenz-Grotesk. It was replaced with Helvetica in later editions.]]\n[[File:KAS-Berlin-Wilmersdorf-Bild-13303-1.jpg|thumb|Political debate, [[West Berlin]], 1970]]\nBesides uses in Swiss-style poster design, Akzidenz-Grotesk and Georgia are the official fonts of the [[American Red Cross]].<ref name=\"http://www.rockriver.redcross.org/media/Brand_Standards.pdf\">[http://www.rockriver.redcross.org/media/Brand_Standards.pdf American Red Cross Brand Standards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812094946/http://www.rockriver.redcross.org/media/Brand_Standards.pdf |date=2010-08-12 }}</ref> Akzidenz-Grotesk is also the font used in [[Arizona State University]]'s brand logo.<ref name=\"https://commguide.asu.edu/downloads/fonts\">[https://commguide.asu.edu/downloads/fonts Arizona State University Communication Guide | Font Standard]</ref>\n\nBerthold sued [[Target Corporation]] for copyright infringement and breach of contract in 2017, alleging that Target had asked a design firm to use the font in a promotional video without a license.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/commercialcontracts/articles/971652/chicago-font-co-takes-aim-at-target-s-use-of-typeface/|title=Chicago Font Co. Takes Aim at Target's Use Of Typeface \u2013 Law360|website=www.law360.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-06}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Berthold typesetting systems#Berthold ADS (Akzidenz Dialog System)|Berthold Akzidenz Dialog System]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Frutiger|first1=Adrian|authorlink1=Adrian Frutiger|editor1-last=Osterer|editor1-first=Heiden|editor2-last=Stamm|editor2-first=Philipp|title=Typefaces: The Complete Works|date=2009|publisher=Birkh\u00e4user|location=Basel|isbn=978-3764385811|edition=English}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Gerstner|first1=Karl|authorlink1=Karl Gerstner|title=Die alte Akzidenz-Grotesk auf neuer Basis|journal=Der Druckspiegel|date=1963|url=http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/akzidenz-grotesk-auf-neuer-basis-german-original.pdf|accessdate=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015202204/http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/akzidenz-grotesk-auf-neuer-basis-german-original.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-15|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hollis|first=Richard|title=Swiss Graphic Design: The Origins and Growth of an International Style, 1920\u20131965|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7XO-LMDo4yQC&pg=PA201|year=2006|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|isbn=978-1-85669-487-2}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Homola|first1=Wolfgang|title=Type design in the age of the machine. The \u2018Breite Grotesk\u2019 by J. G. Schelter & Giesecke|url=http://www.typefacedesign.org/resources/dissertation/2004/WolfgangHomola_dissertation.pdf|date=2004|publisher=University of Reading (archived)|accessdate=17 January 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112014111/http://www.typefacedesign.org/resources/dissertation/2004/WolfgangHomola_dissertation.pdf|archivedate=12 January 2011}}\n* {{cite book |last1=M\u00fcller|first1=Lars|last2=Malsy|first2=Victor|last3=Kupferschmid|first3=Indra|title=Helvetica Forever: Story of a Typeface|date=2009|publisher=Lars M\u00fcller|isbn=978-3037781210}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=The godfather: retracing the origins of Akzidenz-Grotesk |journal=Footnotes |date=2019 |issue=3 |}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Schriftk\u00fcnstler \u2013 A historiographic examination of the relationship between handcraft and art regarding the design and making of printers\u2019 type in Germany between 1871 and 1914 |date=2020 |publisher=Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Braunschweig (PhD thesis) |url=https://www.academia.edu/42108215/Chapter_1_Schriftku_nstler_A_historiographic_examination_of_the_relationship_between_handcraft_and_art_regarding_the_design_and_making_of_printers_type_in_Germany_between_1871_and_1914 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |chapter=Chapter 1}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Schriftk\u00fcnstler \u2013 A historiographic examination of the relationship between handcraft and art regarding the design and making of printers\u2019 type in Germany between 1871 and 1914 |date=2020 |publisher=Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Braunschweig (PhD thesis) |url=https://www.academia.edu/42363074/Chapter_2_Research_methods._From_Schriftku_nstler_A_historiographic_examination_of_the_relationship_between_handcraft_and_art_regarding_the_design_and_making_of_printers_type_in_Germany_between_1871_and_1914 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |chapter=Chapter 2: Research methods}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Schriftk\u00fcnstler \u2013 A historiographic examination of the relationship between handcraft and art regarding the design and making of printers\u2019 type in Germany between 1871 and 1914 |date=2020 |publisher=Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Braunschweig (PhD thesis) |url=https://www.academia.edu/42367851/Chapter_3_Writing_history_as_a_designer._From_Schriftku_nstler_A_historiographic_examination_of_the_relationship_between_handcraft_and_art_regarding_the_design_and_making_of_printers_type_in_Germany_between_1871_and_1914 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |chapter=Chapter 3: Writing history as a designer}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Schriftk\u00fcnstler \u2013 A historiographic examination of the relationship between handcraft and art regarding the design and making of printers\u2019 type in Germany between 1871 and 1914 |date=2020 |publisher=Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Braunschweig (PhD thesis) |url=https://www.academia.edu/42732982/Chapter_6_Type_design_in_German_foundries_from_1871_to_1914._From_Schriftku_nstler_A_historiographic_examination_of_the_relationship_between_handcraft_and_art_regarding_the_design_and_making_of_printers_type_in_Germany_between_1871_and_1914 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |chapter=Chapter 6: Type design in German foundries from 1871 to 1914}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Schwemer-Scheddin|first=Yvonne|title=Sonderheft G\u00fcnter Gerhard Lange|journal=Typografische Monatsbl\u00e4tter|date=2003}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tracy|first=Walter|author-link=Walter Tracy|title=Letters of Credit: A View of Type Design|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8NssjbqNcsC&pg=PA194|date=2003|publisher=D.R. Godine|isbn=978-1-56792-240-0}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*Berthold pages: [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book/proplus/ AG Book Pro+], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book-rounded/proplus/ AG Book Rounded], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book-stencil-et-al/pro/ AG Book Stencil et al], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-old-face/pro/ AG Old Face], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-schoolbook/pro/ AG Schoolbook], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/akzidenz-grotesk/proplus/ Akzidenz-Grotesk Pro+], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/akzidenz-grotesk-next-family/pro/ Akzidenz-Grotesk Next]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719030422/http://www.sanskritweb.net/fontdocs/#Akzidenz Akzidenz Grotesk sample books] digitised by Ulrich Stiehl\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/n1ke/albums/72157629429950223 Berthold specimens from c. 1913], showing Schattierte-Grotesk and co-branding mentioning Berthold and Bauer\n* ''Fonts in Use'' coverage: [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/76/akzidenz-grotesk Akzidenz-Grotesk], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/31705/akzidenz-grotesk-condensed AG Condensed], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/7248/ag-book AG Book], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/574/standard Standard] (for American uses)\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/stewf/sets/72157661987768480 Probe 429A] (c. 1960 specimen, photographed by Stephen Coles/Thomas Maier)\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/101656904@N05/sets/72157679746685343 Berthold exklusiv 013: Akzidenz-Grotesk] (1980s Berthold specimen, for phototypesetting)\n* [http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GG/1937-08-01/edition/null/page/5 Berthold advertisement from 1937] not showing Akzidenz-Grotesk. The advert showcases \"modern and successful\" faces, illustrating the eclipse of Akzidenz-Grotesk in this period.\n* [http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GG/1959-01-01/edition/null/page/68 1959 advert] announcing the arrival of Akzidenz-Grotesk on the Linotype hot metal system\n\n[[Category:Berthold typefaces]]\n[[Category:Grotesque sans-serif typefaces]]\n[[Category:Letterpress typefaces]]\n[[Category:Photocomposition typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with infant variants]]\n[[Category:Digital typefaces]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1898]]\n[[Category:Linotype typefaces]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox font\n| name = Akzidenz-Grotesk\n| image = AkzidenzGroteskspecAIB1.svg\n| style = [[Sans-serif]]\n| classifications = [[Sans-serif#Grotesque|Grotesque]]\n| date =\n| foundry = [[H. Berthold AG]]<ref name=\"The 1869\u20131978 headquarters of Berthold today\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=The 1869\u20131978 headquarters of Berthold today |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2018/04/the-1869-1978-headquarters-of-berthold-today/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n| releasedate = 1898\n}}\n'''Akzidenz-Grotesk''' is a [[sans-serif]] [[typeface]] family originally released by the [[Berthold Type Foundry]] of [[Berlin]]. ''Akzidenz'' indicates its intended use as a typeface for commercial, or \"occasional\" or \"jobbing\", print runs such as publicity, tickets and forms,<ref name=\"Klim New details\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=New details about the origins of Akzidenz-Grotesk |url=https://klim.co.nz/blog/new-details-about-origins-akzidenz-grotesk/ |publisher=[[Klim Type Foundry]] |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref> as opposed to [[fine press|fine printing]], and \"grotesque\" was a standard name for sans-serif typefaces at the time.\n\nOriginating during the late nineteenth century, Akzidenz-Grotesk belongs to a tradition of general-purpose, unadorned sans-serif types that had become dominant in German printing during the nineteenth century. Relatively little-known for a half-century after its introduction, it achieved iconic status in the [[post-war period]] as the preferred typeface of many [[Switzerland|Swiss]] graphic designers in what became called the [[International Typographic Style|'International' or 'Swiss' design style]] which became popular across the [[Western world]] in the 1950s and 1960s. Its simple, neutral design has also influenced many later typefaces. It has sometimes been sold as '''Standard''' or '''Basic Commercial''' in English-speaking countries.\n==Design characteristics==\n[[Image:Akzidenz-Grotesk variations.svg|thumb|Digital variants of Akzidenz-Grotesk, showing the slight inconsistencies and idiosyncrasies between different weights and widths]]\nLike most [[sans-serif]]s, Akzidenz-Grotesk is 'monoline' in structure, with all strokes of the letter of similar width. This gives a sense of simplicity and an absence of the adornment and [[Swash (typography)|flourishes]] seen in the more decorative sans-serifs of the late nineteenth century influenced by the [[Art Nouveau]] style.{{sfn|Homola|2004|p=29}} Modern type designer [[Martin Majoor]] has described the general design of Akzidenz-Grotesk and its ancestors as similar in letterforms to the [[Didone (typography)|Didone]] serif fonts that were standard printing types in the nineteenth century, such as [[Didot (typeface)|Didot]], [[Walbaum (typeface)|Walbaum]] and their followers.<ref name=\"Majoor My Type Design Philosophy\" /> This is most visible in the quite folded-up [[Counter (typography)|apertures]] of letters such as \u2018a\u2019 and \u2018c\u2019.<ref name=\"Majoor My Type Design Philosophy\">{{cite web|last1=Majoor|first1=Martin|author-link=Martin Majoor|title=My Type Design Philosophy|url=http://www.typotheque.com/articles/my_type_design_philosophy|website=Typotheque|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> The capitals of Akzidenz-Grotesk are wide and relatively uniform in width.<ref name=\"A Neo-Grotesque Heritage\" />\n\nThe 'g' of Akzidenz-Grotesk is a 'single-storey' design, like in many other [[Germany|German]] sans-serifs, but unlike the double-storey 'g' found in most serif faces and in many of the earliest sans-serifs that had a lower-case; sans-serif types first appeared in London, but became popular in Germany from the mid-nineteenth century onwards.<ref name=\"Handover Monotype\" /><ref name=\"Unborn: sans serif lower case\">{{cite web|last1=Mosley |first1=James |title=Comments on Typophile thread \u2013 \"Unborn: sans serif lower case in the 19th century\" |url=http://www.typophile.com/node/46184 |website=Typophile (archived) |accessdate=15 October 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628041224/http://www.typophile.com/node/46184|author-link=James Mosley|archivedate=28 June 2014 }}</ref> [[Walter Tracy]] describes this style of 'g' as a common feature in German sans-serifs of the period and apparently influenced by the tradition of [[blackletter]], still [[Antiqua-Fraktur dispute|very popular]] for printing extended texts in Germany in the late nineteenth century, which uses a single-storey 'g' in upright composition.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=58}}\n\nAs is normal in typefaces cut during the metal type period, Akzidenz-Grotesk shows variation between sizes of metal type, with adaptation of letter-spacing and proportions to different sizes.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" /> In addition, there is variation between weights: [[Karl Gerstner]] notes that even comparing one size (20pt), the medium and bold weights have different [[x-height]], cap height and descender length to the light and regular weights.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" />{{efn|Berthold literature from the 1900s marketed the light and regular weights (light at the time under the name of 'Royal-Grotesk') as being compatible; see below.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe AfB 1904\" />}} This is common with nineteenth-century sans-serifs, which were not designed with the intention of forming an extended family that would match together.<ref name=\"Knockout\">{{cite web|last1=Hoefler|first1=Jonathan|last2=Frere-Jones|first2=Tobias|authorlink1=Jonathan Hoefler|authorlink2=Tobias Frere-Jones|title=Knockout|url=https://www.typography.com/fonts/knockout/design-notes|publisher=[[Hoefler & Co]]|accessdate=21 October 2017|quote=The notion of the \"type family\" is so central to typography that it's easy to forget how recent an invention it is. Throughout most of its history, typography simply evolved the forms that were the most useful and the most interesting, generally with indifference toward how they related to one another. Italic faces existed for decades before they were considered as companions for romans, just as poster types shouted in a range of emphatic tones before they were reimagined as \"bold\" or \"condensed\" cousins. The notion that a type family should be planned from the outset is a Modernist concoction, and it's one that type designers have lived with for less than a century\u2026For more than a century before Helvetica, the sans serif landscape was dominated by unrelated designs.}}</ref><ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> The differences in proportions between different sizes and weights of Akzidenz-Grotesk has led to a range of contemporary adaptations, reviving or modifying different aspects of the original design, discussed below.\n\n==Early history==\n[[File:Schattierte Grotesk 1896.jpg|thumb|right|The release of Akzidenz-Grotesk was not well-documented in contemporary printing literature. However, it seems to derive from this shadowed sans-serif (\"schattierte Grotesk\") from Bauer & Co. of Stuttgart, reviewed in 1896.<ref name=\"Schriftprobenschau 1896\" />]]  \n[[File:Berthold Sweden advertisement.jpg|thumb|right|A 1905 advertisement for Berthold in a Swedish printing journal, offering Royal-Grotesk, later branded as the light weight of Akzidenz-Grotesk, for sale. The sans-serif type is used in a secondary role underneath a more decorative heading face.<ref name=\"Berthold advertisement Alm\u00e4nna Svenska Boktryckaref\u00f6reningens Meddelanden\">{{cite journal |title=Berthold advertisement |journal=Alm\u00e4nna Svenska Boktryckaref\u00f6reningens Meddelanden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vp0TAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA368|date=1905 |pages=106, 336, 368}}</ref>{{efn|The display face appears to be Berthold's Herold.<ref name=\"Reklameschrift Herold FIU\">{{cite web |title=Reklameschrift Herold |url=https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/20935/herold |website=Fonts in Use |accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref>}}]]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk's design descends from a school of general-purpose sans-serifs cut in the nineteenth century.<ref name=\"Shinn Uniformity\">{{cite journal |last1=Shinn |first1=Nick |authorlink1=Nick Shinn |title=The Face of Uniformity |journal=Graphic Exchange |date=2003 |url=http://shinntype.com/wp-content/uploads/Uniformity.pdf |accessdate=31 December 2019}}</ref> Sans-serifs had become very popular in Germany by the late nineteenth century, which had a large number of small local [[Type foundry|type foundries]] offering different versions.<ref name=\"Distribution of sans serif typefaces across German-speaking foundries in the 19th century\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Distribution of sans serif typefaces across German-speaking foundries in the 19th century |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2018/06/distribution-sans-serif-typefaces-across-german-speaking-foundries-19th-century/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Handover Monotype\" /> Berthold literature from the 1920s dated the design to 1898,<ref name=\"Handbuch der Schriftarten\" /><ref name=\"Handover Monotype\">{{cite journal|last1=Handover|first1=Phyllis Margaret|author-link=P. M. Handover|title=Grotesque Letters|journal=Monotype Newsletter, also printed in Motif as \"Letters without Serifs\"|url=http://up.stewf.com/0o400K3p302U|date=1958}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\" /> when the firm registered two [[design patent]]s on the family.<ref name=\"Godfather Reynolds\">{{cite journal |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=The godfather: retracing the origins of Akzidenz-Grotesk |journal=Footnotes |date=2019 |issue=3 |pages=134\u2013143}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds design patent\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Note on the original design patent for Akzidenz-Grotesk |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/08/note-on-the-original-design-patent-for-akzidenz-grotesk/ |website=TypeOff |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nRecent research by Eckehart Schumacher-Gebler, Indra Kupferschmid and Dan Reynolds has clarified many aspects of Akzidenz-Grotesk's history. The source of Akzidenz-Grotesk appears to be Berthold's 1897 purchase of the Bauer u. Cie Type Foundry of [[Stuttgart]] (not to be confused with the much better-known [[Bauer Type Foundry]] of [[Frankfurt]]); Kupferschmid concludes that the design appears to be related to a shadowed sans-serif ('Schattierte Grotesk') sold by the Bauer Foundry and reviewed in a printing journal in 1896.<ref name=\"Schriftprobenschau 1896\" /> Two design patents on Akzidenz-Grotesk were filed in April 1898, first on the 14th in Stuttgart by Bauer and then on the 28th in Berlin by Berthold, leading Reynolds to conclude that the design was executed in Stuttgart.<ref name=\"Reynolds design patent\" /> Some early adverts that present Akzidenz-Grotesk are co-signed by both brands.<ref name=\"JongPurvis2005\">{{cite book|author1=Cees W. de Jong|author2=Alston W. Purvis|author3=Friedrich Friedl|title=Creative Type: A Sourcebook of Classic and Contemporary Letterforms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mDhXoYIGTFAC&pg=PA331|year=2005|publisher=Inmerc|isbn=978-90-6611-250-6|page=331}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2a timeline\" /><ref>{{cite book |last1=Wanetzky |first1=Harald |title=Typotektur: Architektur und Typografie im 20. Jahrhundert : der Modellfall einer Zusammenf\u00fchrung |date=1995 |quote=Berthold und Bauer werben im Jahre 1899 mit einem aus heutiger Sicht seltsam anmutenden [[Jugendstil]]layout f\u00fcr die 'Accidenz-Grotesk'.}}</ref> Early references to Akzidenz-Grotesk at Berthold often use the alternative spelling 'Accidenz-Grotesk'; Reynolds suggests that the name may have been intended as a [[brand extension]] following on from an \"Accidenz-Gothisch\" blackletter face sold by the Bauer & Co. foundry.<ref name=\"Reynolds name source\">{{cite web|last1=Reynolds|first1=Dan|title=Also, the name Accidenz-Grotesk likely came from Bauer & Co., too. That foundry's founder F.W. Bauer had earlier cut a typeface called Accidenz-Gothisch|url=https://twitter.com/typeoff/status/920211001097801729|website=Twitter|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\">{{cite web|last1=Spiekermann |first1=Erik|author-link1=Erik Spiekermann|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk (Re-)Release Dates (comments on Typophile thread)|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628041224/http://www.typophile.com/node/17643 |website=Typophile (archived) |accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref> In general, Reynolds comments that the style of Schattierte Grotesk and Akzidenz-Grotesk \"seem to me to be more of a synthesis of then-current ideas of sans serif letterform design, rather than copies of any specific products from other firms.\"<ref name=\"Klim New details\" />\n\nThe light weight of Akzidenz-Grotesk was for many years branded separately as 'Royal-Grotesk'. It apparently was cut by Berthold around 1902-3, when it was announced in a trade periodical as \"a new, quite usable typeface\" and advertised as having matching dimensions allowing it to be combined with the regular weight of Akzidenz-Grotesk.<ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\" /><ref name=\"Schriftprobe AfB 1903\">{{cite journal|title=Schriftprobe|journal=Archiv f\u00fcr Buchgewerbe|date=1903|volume=40|page=19|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cDsgAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA19|accessdate=22 December 2017|quote=Eine neue recht verwendbare Schrift hat die Firma H. Berthold Akt.-Ges in Berlin geschaffen, eine in acht Graden geschnittene Royal-Grotesk, die sich zu allen besseren Accidenzen verwenden lassen und infolge ihres scharfen und sauberen Schnitts zur besten Wirkung gelangen wird. Auf eine kleine, vielleicht unbeabsichtigte Unsch\u00f6nheit m\u00f6chten wir doch hinweisen. Diese betrifft das Versal-R, dessen Querstrich zu tief steht, was auff\u00e4llt und st\u00f6rend wirkt, wenn der Buchstabe zwischen B und E steht. Vielleicht ist hier eine Verbesserung noch ang\u00e4ngig. Chronos.}}</ref><ref name=\"Schriftprobe AfB 1904\">{{cite journal|title=Schriftprobe|journal=Archiv f\u00fcr Buchgewerbe|date=1904|volume=41|page=149|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OTwgAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA149|accessdate=22 December 2017|quote=Die Firma H. Berthold, Akt-Ges. in Berlin zeigt in einem h\u00fcbsch angeordneten handlichen Heftchen zwei Garnituren Royal- und Akzidenz-Grotesk, beide sich erg\u00e4nzende Schriften von vornehmer Wirkung, die um so mehr als zeitgem\u00e4\u00df bezeichnet werden k\u00f6nnen, weil anscheinend nun endlich auch in der Druckausstattung der Akzidenzen Wege eingeschlagen werden, die zu einer wesentlichen Vereinfachung des Satzbildes f\u00fchren d\u00fcrften.}}</ref><ref name=\"Handbuch der Schriftarten\" /> Reynolds and Florian Hardwig have documented the Schmalhalbfett weight (semi-bold, or medium, condensed) to be a family sold by many German type-foundries, which probably originated from a New York type foundry.<ref name=\"Reynolds distribution of sans serifs\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Research update: Distribution of sans serifs in German-speaking foundries during the nineteenth century |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/04/research-update-sans-serifs-type-german-speaking-foundries-nineteenth-century/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Reynolds Longina\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Longina-Schriften |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/typeoff/33857851718/ |website=Flickr |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Mallet Magic\">{{cite web |last1=Hardwig |first1=Florian |last2=Reynolds |first2=Dan |title=Mallet Magic \u2013 Harry Breuer And His Quintet |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/26800/mallet-magic-harry-breuer-and-his-quintet |website=Fonts in Use |accessdate=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[G\u00fcnter Gerhard Lange]], Berthold's post-war artistic director, considered effectively the curator of the Akzidenz-Grotesk design, said in a 2003 interview Akzidenz-Grotesk came from the Ferdinand Theinhardt type foundry, and this claim has been widely copied elsewhere.{{sfn|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=24|ps=:\"Royal-Grotesk was my favourite font from the beginning. I used it on my first Berthold business card and my letterhead. It's a delicate, slender piece of engraving and came from the royal punchcutter Ferdinand Theinhardt. His foundry came to Berthold in 1908. People always talk about how this sans-serif typeface is \"anonymous\", but it's now clear that it's Theinhardt's. Royal-Grotesk was made for royal scientific printing. And Theinhardt added to it the normal, semi-bold and bold. For me those four weights of Akzidenz-Grotesk are the best.\"}} This had been established by businessman and [[punchcutting|punchcutter]] Ferdinand Theinhardt, who was otherwise particularly famous for his scholarly endeavours in the field of [[Egyptian hieroglyphs|hieroglyph]] and [[Syriac alphabet|Syriac]] typefaces; he had sold the business in 1885.<ref name=\"Liste der Hieroglyphischen Typen aus der Schriftgie\u00dferei des Herrn F. Theinhardt in Berlin\">{{cite book|title=Liste der Hieroglyphischen Typen aus der Schriftgie\u00dferei des Herrn F. Theinhardt in Berlin|date=1875|publisher=Buchdruckerei der K\u00f6nigl. Akademie der Wissenschaften (G. Vogt)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U5oNAAAAQAAJ|accessdate=21 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Theinhardt Reynolds hieroglyphic\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=The Academy of Sciences of the USSR's hieroglyphs font (1928) |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/02/the-academy-of-sciences-of-the-ussrs-hieroglyphs-font-1928/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Typeoff Theinhardt locations\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Berlin locations of the old Ferd. Theinhardt foundry |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/02/berlin-locations-of-the-old-ferd-theinhardt-foundry/ |website=Typeoff |accessdate=27 February 2019}}</ref> Professor Indra Kupferschmid, who has researched the early use of sans-serifs in Germany, however reports that this cannot be correct: \"there must have been an Accidenz-Grotesk at Berthold before the acquisition of Theinhardt\u2019s foundry in 1908\",<ref name=\"Some notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid |first1=Indra |title=Some notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk |url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2012/04/ag/ |website=kupferschrift* |accessdate=19 January 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330041347/http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2012/04/ag/ |archivedate=30 March 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\" /><ref>[http://www.typophile.com/node/4567 Akzidenz Grotesk roots]</ref> and confusion may have occurred with fonts held by Berthold that the Theinhardt foundry licensed.<ref name=\"Some notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk\" /><ref name=\"Stefan George Schrift\">{{cite web|last1=Jan-Pool|first1=Albert|title=Stefan George Schrift|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/albert-jan_pool/12100921625/|website=Flickr|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Klingspor Ferdinand Theinhardt\">{{cite web|title=Ferdinand Theinhardt|url=http://www.klingspor-museum.de/KlingsporKuenstler/Schriftdesigner/Theinhardt/FTheinhardt.pdf|publisher=[[Klingspor Museum]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=Some notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk Part 2|url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2017/10/ag-2/|website=kupferschrift|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Schriftprobenschau 1896\">{{cite journal|title=Schriftprobenschau|journal=Archiv f\u00fcr Buchdruckerkunst und verwandte Gesch\u00e4ftszweige|date=1896|pages=404, 407|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gRcDAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA403|quote=Die Schriftgie\u00dferei Bauer & Co., Stuttgart und D\u00fcsseldorf, ver\u00f6ffentlicht unter den heutigen Schriftproben eine schattierte Grotesk und bietet unseren Lesern mit dieser Schrift ein beliebtes, sehr verwendbares Material, das sich in \u00e4hnlicher, \u00e4lterer Ausf\u00fchrung seit jener einen Platz auf allen guten Akzidenzien erhoben hat.}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2a timeline\" /><ref name=\"Dan Reynolds Twitter\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Origin of Akzidenz-Grotesk's weight now sorted. @kupfers was right. Berthold derived it from an earlier Bauer & Co. display typeface. |url=https://twitter.com/typeoff/status/920203429502504965 |website=Twitter |accessdate=7 October 2018 |quote=Origin of Akzidenz-Grotesk's weight now sorted. @kupfers was right. Berthold derived it from an earlier Bauer & Co. display typeface called Schattierte Grotesk. Berthold bought Bauer & Co. The new Berlin + Stuttgart company made an \"unschattierte\" version, which Berthold began selling in 1898 as Accidenz-Grotesk.}}</ref> Reynolds additionally points out that Theinhardt sold his foundry to Oskar Mammen and Robert and Emil Mosig in 1885, a decade before Akzidenz-Grotesk was released, and there is no evidence that he cut any further fonts for them after this year.<ref name=\"Typeoff Theinhardt locations\" /> As Lange commented, it was claimed in the post-war period that Royal-Grotesk's name referred to it being commissioned by the [[Prussian Academy of Sciences]], but Kupferschmid was not able to find it used in its publications.<ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\" /> \n\n[[File:Cologne WWI Notgeld Banknote 10 Pfg 1918 I.jpg|thumb|left|A German banknote from 1918, using a range of sans-serifs of the period]]\nMany other grotesques in a similar style to Akzidenz-Grotesk were sold in Germany during this period. Around the beginning of the twentieth century, these increasingly began to be branded as larger families of multiple matched styles.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> Its competitors included the very popular [[Venus (typeface)|Venus-Grotesk]] of the Bauer foundry of Frankfurt, very similar to Akzidenz-Grotesk but with high-waisted capitals, and Koralle by [[Schelter & Giesecke Type Foundry|Schelter & Giesecke]], which has a single-storey 'a'.<ref name=\"Shaw2017\">{{cite book|author=Paul Shaw|title=Revival Type: Digital Typefaces Inspired by the Past|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n7e0DgAAQBAJ&pg=PA190|date=April 2017|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-21929-6|pages=190\u2013205}}</ref><ref name=\"Koralle Alphabettes\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|title=Koralle|url=http://www.alphabettes.org/koralle/|website=Alphabettes|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Venus - MyFonts\">{{cite web|title=Venus \u2013 MyFonts|url=https://www.myfonts.com/fonts/ftbauer/venus/alternate_cuts.html|website=[[MyFonts]]|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>{{efn|According to Kupferschmid, Ideal-Grotesk, a separate sans-serif face Berthold sold in the first half of the twentieth century, is a Venus knockoff, possibly made by electrotype copying.<ref name=\"Arial addendum no. 3\" />}} ([[Monotype Grotesque|Monotype Grotesque 215]] also is based on German typefaces of this period.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=98}}) Seeman's 1926 ''Handbuch der Schriftarten'' (''Handbook of Typefaces'', a handbook of all the metal typefaces available in Germany, illustrates the wide range of sans-serif typefaces on sale in Germany by the time of its publication.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=58, 92}}<ref name=\"Handbuch der Schriftarten\">{{cite book|title=Handbuch der Schriftarten|date=1926|pages=181\u2013218|publisher=Seemann|location=Leipzig|url=http://www.klingspor-museum.de/Handbuch-der-Schriftarten.html|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> By around 1911, Berthold had begun to market Akzidenz-Grotesk as a complete family.<ref name=\"Berthold specimen c. 1913\">{{cite web|last1='N1KE'|title=Type Specimen book H. Berthold AG, ca 1913|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/n1ke/albums/72157629429950223|website=Flickr|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2\" /><ref name=\"Kupferschmid AG 2a timeline\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=Notes on the history of Akzidenz-Grotesk Part 2a \u2013 Timeline|url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2017/12/ag-timeline/|website=Kupferschrift|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Vogelschau.gif|thumb|The poet [[Stefan George]] commissioned alternate characters for Akzidenz-Grotesk for printing his poetry.]]\nWhile apparently not unpopular, Akzidenz-Grotesk was not among the most intensively-marketed typefaces of the period, and was not even particularly aggressively marketed by Berthold.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /> A 1921 Berthold specimen and company history described it almost apologetically: \"In 1898 Accidenz-Grotesk was created, which has earned a laurel wreath of fame for itself. This old typeface, which these days one would perhaps make in a more modern style, has a peculiar life in its own way which would probably be lost if it were to be altered. All the many imitations of Accidenz-Grotesk have not matched its character.\"<ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\" /> An unusual user of Berthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk in the period soon after its release, however, was the poet [[Stefan George]].<ref name=\"Prophet of doom\">{{cite web |last1=Cartwright |first1=Justin |authorlink1=Justin Cartwright |title=Prophet of doom |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jan/14/featuresreviews.guardianreview11 |website=The Guardian |accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> He commissioned some custom [[Uncial script|uncial-style]] alternate characters to print his poetry.<ref name=\"Burke1998\">{{cite book|author-link=Christopher Burke (design writer)|first=Christopher|last=Burke|title=Paul Renner: The Art of Typography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zfT0Iam0q7AC&pg=PA115|date=December 1998|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=978-1-56898-158-1|pages=115\u20138}}</ref><ref name=\"AurnhammerBraungart2016\">{{cite book|author1=Achim Aurnhammer|author2=Wolfgang Braungart|author3=Stefan Breuer|author4=Ute Oelmann|title=Stefan George und sein Kreis: Ein Handbuch|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OaFlCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA480|date=1 January 2016|publisher=Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG|isbn=978-3-11-045688-2|pages=480\u2013481}}</ref><ref name=\"Gewerblicher Rechtsschutz und Urheberrecht Zeitschrift\">{{cite book |title=Gewerblicher Rechtsschutz und Urheberrecht Zeitschrift |date=1943 |page=45 |quote=Gedruckt wurde seit 1904 in der sogenannten Stefan-George-Schrift, einer Letternschrift, die der Graphiker Melchior Lechter im Jahre 1903 in Anlehnung an die Handschrift Georges aus einer freien Akzidenz-Grotesk-Schrift der Schriftgie\u00dferei Berthold, Berlin, geschaffen hatte. Stefan George ist 1933, Melchior Lechtor 1938 gestorben.}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Mid-twentieth-century use==\n[[File:Geisser Plakat Mohrenball 1969.jpg|thumb|left|A 1969 poster exemplifying the trend of the 1950s and 60s: solid red colour, simplified images and the use of a grotesque face. This design, by Robert Geisser, appears to use Helvetica.]]\n[[File:1959 - Kunsthalle Basel - 4 Bildhauer.jpg|right|thumb|Art exhibition poster by Armin Hofmann, 1959]]\nThe use of Akzidenz-Grotesk and similar \"grotesque\" typefaces dipped from the late 1920s due to the arrival of fashionable new [[Sans-serif#Geometric|\"geometric\" sans-serifs]] such as [[Erbar (typeface)|Erbar]], [[Futura (typeface)|Futura]] and [[Kabel (typeface)|Kabel]], based on the proportions of the circle and square. Berthold released its own family in this style, Berthold-Grotesk.{{efn|Berthold-Grotesk is somewhat less well-known than other German geometrics of the period. A licensed adaptation (changing some characters) by the Amsterdam Type Foundry under the name of [[Nobel (typeface)|Nobel]], however, became a popular standard typeface in Dutch printing.<ref name=\"Dutch Typefounders' Specimens\">{{cite book|last1=Lane|first1=John A.|last2=Lommen|first2=Mathieu|last3=de Zoete|first3=Johan|title=Dutch Typefounders' Specimens|date=1998|publisher=De Graaf|pages=29\u201331|url=https://issuu.com/bijzondere_collecties_uva/docs/1998_dutch_typefounders_specimens|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Middendorp2004\">{{cite book|first=Jan |last=Middendorp|title=Dutch Type|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sR9g5xPPJVQC&pg=PA45|year=2004|publisher=010 Publishers|isbn=978-90-6450-460-0|page=45}}</ref> Some twentieth-century sources used different terminology to distinguish between the traditional \"grotesques/gothics\" and the new faces of the 1920s, such as restricting the term \"sans-serifs\" to the latter group.<ref name=\"The Typography of Press Advertisement\">{{cite book|last1=Day|first1=Kenneth|title=The Typography of Press Advertisement|pages=86\u20138, etc.|date=1956}}</ref> The term \"industrial\" has also been used for the early grotesque sans-serifs like Akzidenz-Grotesk.{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=98}}}} \n\nHowever, during this period there was increasing interest in using sans-serifs as capturing the spirit of the time, most famously, [[Jan Tschichold]]'s influential book ''Die Neue Typographie'', which praised the aesthetic qualities of the \"anonymous\" sans-serifs of the nineteenth century{{sfn|Tracy|2003|p=96}} and was printed in a sans-serif similar to Berthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk.{{efn|Although similar, according to Kupferschmid the type used in ''Die Neue Typographie'' is not Berthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk.<ref name=\"Live Type Research in Barcelona\">{{cite web |last1=Kupferschmid |first1=Indra |title=Live Type Research in Barcelona |url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2014/09/live-type-research-in-barcelona/ |website=Kupferschrift |accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>}} Its comments would prove influential in later graphic design: \n\n<blockquote>Among all the types that are available, the so-called \"Grotesque\"...is the only one in spiritual accordance with our time. To proclaim sans-serif as the typeface of our time is not a question of being fashionable, it really does express the same tendencies to be seen in our architecture\u2026there is no doubt that the sans-serif types available today are not yet wholly satisfactory as all-purpose faces. The essential characteristics of this type have not been fully worked out: the lower-case letters especially are still too like their \"humanistic\" counterparts. Most of them, in particular the newest designs such as Erbar and Kabel, are inferior to the old anonymous sans-serifs, and have modifications which place them basically in line with the rest of the \"art\" faces. As bread-and-butter faces they are less good than the old sans faces...I find the best face in use today is the so-called ordinary jobbing sanserif, which is quiet and easy to read.<ref name=\"The New Typography\">{{cite book |last1=Tschichold |first1=Jan |authorlink1=Jan Tschichold |editor1-last=McLean |editor1-first=Ruari |editor2-last=Kinross |editor2-first=Robin |editor1-link=Ruari McLean |editor2-link=Robin Kinross |title=The New Typography: a handbook for modern designers |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=0520071476}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn the post-war period and particularly in Switzerland a revival in Akzidenz-Grotesk's popularity took hold, in what became known as the \"Swiss International Style\" of graphic design. This style often contrasted Akzidenz-Grotesk with photographic art, and did not use [[all caps]] as much as many older posters.<ref name=\"Eskilson2012\" /> Graphic designers of this style, such as Karl Gerstner, [[Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann]] and [[Armin Hofmann]], all used Akzidenz-Grotesk heavily.<ref name=\"Reputations: Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann\">{{cite web |last1=Schwemer-Scheddin |first1=Yvonne |title=Reputations: Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann |url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/reputations-josef-muller-brockmann |website=Eye |accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Raposo Swiss Automobile Club\">{{cite web |last1=Raposo |first1=T\u00e2nia |title=Campaign posters for the Swiss Automobile Club |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/4263/campaign-posters-for-the-swiss-automobile-clu |website=Fonts In Use |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Coles Z\u00fcrich Town Hall\">{{cite web |last1=Coles |first1=Stephen |title=Posters for the Zurich Town Hall |url=https://fontsinuse.com/uses/1329/posters-for-the-zurich-town-hall |website=Fonts In Use |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" /> Like Tschichold, Gerstner argued that the sans-serifs of the nineteenth-century were more \"matter-of-fact\" than the more \"personal\" recent sans-serifs of the previous decades.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\">{{cite journal|last1=Gerstner|first1=Karl|authorlink1=Karl Gerstner|title=A new basis for the old Akzidenz-Grotesk (English translation)|journal=Der Druckspiegel|date=1963|url=http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/a-new-basis-for-akzidenz-grotesk-english-translation.pdf|accessdate=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015202441/http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/a-new-basis-for-akzidenz-grotesk-english-translation.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-15|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Gerstner German\">{{cite journal|last1=Gerstner|first1=Karl|authorlink1=Karl Gerstner|title=Die alte Akzidenz-Grotesk auf neuer Basis|journal=Der Druckspiegel|date=1963|url=http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/akzidenz-grotesk-auf-neuer-basis-german-original.pdf|accessdate=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015202204/http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/akzidenz-grotesk-auf-neuer-basis-german-original.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Art historian Stephen Eskilson wrote that they \"conveyed the functionalist ethos without appearing too stylised...in the manner of the more geometrically pure types.\"<ref name=\"Eskilson2012\" />\n\n[[File:1959 - Gewerbemuseum Basel - Alte und neue Formen in Japan.jpg|thumb|left| 1959 poster by [[Armin Hofmann]] for Japanese exhibition]]\n[[File:Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann 1957.jpg|thumb|right|Classical music concert poster by [[Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann]], 1957]]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk was popular in this period although other typefaces such as Monotype Grotesque were used also: a problem with use of Akzidenz-Grotesk up to the late 1950s was that it was only available in [[metal type|foundry type]] for handsetting. While this was acceptable for posters, by the 1950s [[hot metal typesetting]] machines had become the main system for printing general-purpose body text, and for this system Akzidenz-Grotesk was unavailable until around 1958,{{efn|Date according to ''Helvetica Forever'' and Ulrich Stiehl shows Linotype sales material saying that it was \"taken over to the Linotype machine\" in 1958, although Eskilson reports 1959 for its release.<ref name=\"Helvetica Forever\">{{cite book|last1=M\u00fcller|first1=Lars|last2=Malsy|first2=Victor|last3=Kupferschmid|first3=Indra|title=Helvetica Forever: Story of a Typeface|date=2009|publisher=Lars M\u00fcller|isbn=978-3037781210}}</ref><ref name=\"Akzidenz-Grotesk auf der Linotype-Zeilengu\u00dfmaschine (German)\">{{cite web|last1=Stiehl|first1=Ulrich|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk auf der Linotype-Zeilengu\u00dfmaschine (German)|url=http://www.sanskritweb.net/fontdocs/lino1958.pdf|website=Sanskritweb (blog)|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref>}} when it was first sold on Linotype and then in 1960 on Intertype systems.<ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\">{{cite journal|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk f\u00fcr Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)|journal=Gebrauchsgrafik|date=1959|page=56|url=http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GG/1959-01-01/edition/null/page/68|publisher=Berthold/Linotype (advert)|quote=Die Akzidenz-Grotesk is sechzig Jahre alt, und doch scheint sie nicht zu veraltern, sondern in ihrer Frische und Lebendigkeit f\u00fcr immer zu verharren. Sie erfreut sich solcher Beliebheit, da\u00df sie nun auf die Setzmaschine kam. Zusammen mit den Handsatz-Garnituren bilden die Linotype-Werkschiftgrade eine sehr stattliche Familie, die der Gestalter und Drucker oft und gern bei seiner Arbeit in Anspruch nehmen wird.}}</ref><ref name=\"The Birth of a Giant\" /> Much printing around this time of body text accordingly used Monotype Grotesque as a lookalike.<ref name=\"Hollis2006 Monotype Grotesque\">{{cite book|author=Richard Hollis|title=Swiss Graphic Design: The Origins and Growth of an International Style, 1920\u20131965|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7XO-LMDo4yQC&pg=PA201|year=2006|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|isbn=978-1-85669-487-2|page=201}}</ref><ref name=\"Lees-Maffei2015\">{{cite book|author=Grace Lees-Maffei|title=Iconic Designs: 50 Stories about 50 Things|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qsPuBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA81|date=8 January 2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-0-85785-353-0|pages=81\u20133}}</ref><ref name=\"Roberts2005\">{{cite book|author=Lucienne Roberts|title=Drip-dry Shirts: The Evolution of the Graphic Designer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x2n7ufDeXf8C&pg=PA27|date=1 November 2005|publisher=AVA Publishing|isbn=978-2-940373-08-6|pages=27\u201329}}</ref><ref name=\"Arial addendum no. 3\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|last2=Kupferschmid|first2=Indra|title=Blue Pencil no. 18\u2014Arial addendum no. 3|url=http://www.paulshawletterdesign.com/2011/10/blue-pencil-no-18%E2%80%94arial-addendum-no-3/|website=Paul Shaw Letter Design (blog)|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> In the United States, Akzidenz-Grotesk was imported by Amsterdam Continental Types under the name 'Standard', and became quite popular. According to [[Paul Shaw (design historian)|Paul Shaw]], \"exactly when Amsterdam Continental began importing Standard is unclear but it appears on several record album covers as early as 1957.\"<ref name=\"Helvetica and the New York City Subway AIGA\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|title=The (Mostly) True Story of Helvetica and the New York City Subway|url=https://www.aiga.org/the-mostly-true-story-of-helvetica-and-the-new-york-city-subway|website=AIGA|quote= Exactly when Amsterdam Continental began importing Standard is unclear but it appears on several record album covers as early as 1957.|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Amsterdam Continental: A Handbook of Types\">{{cite web|last1=Devroye|first1=Luc|title=Amsterdam Continental: A Handbook of Types|url=http://luc.devroye.org/Amsterdam-Continental-AHandbookOfTypes.pdf|website=Type Design Information|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Vintage Fonts: 35 Adverts\">{{cite web|last1=Budrick|first1=Callie|title=Vintage Fonts: 35 Adverts From the Past|url=http://www.printmag.com/typography/vintage-fonts-35-adverts-from-the-past/|website=Print|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1957, three notable competitors of Akzidenz-Grotesk appeared intended to compete with its growing popularity: [[Helvetica]] from the Haas foundry, with a very high x-height and a strong image with tight letterspacing, [[Univers]] from [[Deberny & Peignot]], with a large range of weights and widths, and [[Folio (typeface)|Folio]] from Bauer.<ref name=\"The Birth of a Giant\" /> Shaw suggests that Helvetica \"began to muscle out\" Akzidenz-Grotesk in New York from around summer 1965, when Amsterdam Continental's marketing stopped pushing Standard strongly and began to focus on Helvetica instead.<ref name=\"Helvetica and Standard Shaw\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|title=From the Archives no. 15\u2014Helvetica and Standard|url=http://www.paulshawletterdesign.com/2011/03/from-the-archives-no-15%E2%80%94helvetica-and-standard/|website=Paul Shaw Letter Design (blog)|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy the 1960s, Berthold could claim in its type specimens that Akzidenz-Grotesk was:<blockquote>a type series which has proved itself in practice for more than 70 years and has held its ground to the present day against all comers...wherever one sees graphics and advertising of an international standard...starting a revival in Switzerland in recent years, Akzidenz-Grotesk has progressed all over the world and impressed its image in the typography of our time.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\">{{cite book|title=Schriftprobe Nr. 473|date=c. 1966|publisher=H. Berthold/Zweigwerk Stuttgart|url=http://www.sanskritweb.net/fontdocs/|location=Berlin/Stuttgart}}</ref><ref name=\"Probe 429A\">{{cite book|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk von Berthold, Probe 429A (digitisation: Stephen Coles/Thomas Maier)|date=c. 1960|publisher=H. Berthold|location=Stuttgart|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/stewf/sets/72157661987768480|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref></blockquote> \n{{clear}}\n\n==Post-metal releases==\n[[File:Parsons Bl IND td 15.jpg|thumb|Signage on the [[New York City Subway]] in [[Screen printing|screen-printed]] Akzidenz-Grotesk (top) and Helvetica (below)]]\nWith the end of mass use of metal type, Akzidenz-Grotesk has been rereleased and adapted in versions for the new [[phototypesetting]] and digital technologies. \n\nContemporary versions of Akzidenz-Grotesk descend from a late-1950s project, directed by G\u00fcnter Gerhard Lange at Berthold, to enlarge the typeface family. This added new styles including AG Extra (1958), AG Extra Bold (1966) and AG Super (1968), AG Super Italic (2001) and Extra Bold italic (2001).<ref name=\"Jong Sans Serif\">{{cite book|last1=de Jong|first1=Cees W.|title=Sans Serif: The Ultimate Sourcebook of Classic and Contemporary Sans Serif Typography|date=2006|publisher=Thames & Hudson|location=London|isbn=9780500513118|page=23}}</ref><ref name=\"Akzidenz-Grotesk blog\">{{cite web|title=Akzidenz-Grotesk|url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/blog/2010-12-08/akzidenz-grotesk/|website=Berthold Types blog|publisher=H. Berthold|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> \n\nSeparately, Gerstner and other designers at his company GGK Basel launched a project in the 1960s to build Akzidenz-Grotesk into a coherent series, to match the new families appearing in the same style; it was used by Berthold for its Diatype system in the late 60s under the name of \"Gerstner-Programm\" but according to Lange it was never fully released.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" /><ref name=\"FIU Gerstner-Programm\">{{cite web|title=Gerstner-Programm|url=https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/39674/gerstner-programm|website=Fonts in Use|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=26}} A digitisation has been released by the digital type foundry Forgotten Shapes.<ref name=\"Forgotten Shapes Gerstner-Programm\">{{cite web |last1=Raabe |first1=Marcel |title=Gerstner-Programm |url=https://forgotten-shapes.com/gerstner-programm?article=gerstner-programm |publisher=Forgotten Shapes |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe current holder of the Berthold rights is Berthold Types of Chicago, following the bankruptcy of H. Berthold AG of Germany in 1993.<ref name=\"Berthold Goes Bankrupt\">{{cite web|title=Berthold Goes Bankrupt|url=https://www.telecompaper.com/news/berthold-goes-bankrupt--4639|website=Telecompaper|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Harvey Hunt 2004 statement\">{{cite web|last1=Hunt|first1=Harvey|title=Erik Spiekermann's Statements re Berthold|url=http://www.typophile.com/node/5063|website=Typophile|publisher=Berthold Types|accessdate=20 October 2017|date=2004}}</ref> Berthold released Akzidenz-Grotesk in [[OpenType]] format in 2006, under the name Akzidenz-Grotesk Pro, and added matching Cyrillic and Greek characters the next year.<ref>[http://www.creativepro.com/story/news/24218.html Berthold Announces the Release of Akzidenz-Grotesk in OpenType Format] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060518120415/http://www.creativepro.com/story/news/24218.html |date=2006-05-18 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.microsoft.com/typography/links/news.aspx?NID=5786 AG goes Greek and Cyrillic]</ref> Unofficial digitisations have been made by other companies under alternative names.\n==Reception==\nAs described above, many influential graphic designers have used Akzidenz-Grotesk. In 2013, [[Pentagram (design firm)|Pentagram]] partner Domenic Lippa rated Akzidenz-Grotesk as \"probably the best typeface ever designed...it doesn\u2019t overdominate when used, allowing the designer more freedom and versatility\".<ref name=\"Lippa 2013\">{{cite web |last1=Lippa |first1=Domenic |title=The 10 best fonts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/gallery/2013/sep/14/the-10-best-fonts |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> [[Kris Sowersby]] has written that he found the semi-bold and bold weights most satisfying.<ref name=\"Sowersby S\u00f6hne design information\" /> Lange commented that the light weight \"was my favourite font from the beginning. I used it on my first Berthold business card and my letterhead. It's a delicate, slender piece of engraving.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=24}}</ref>\n\nA particular criticism of Akzidenz-Grotesk however, has often been that the regular weight has its rather wide capitals that look unbalanced relative to the lower-case, which is problematic in extended text: Adrian Frutiger commented that Akzidenz-Grotesk forms \"patches in print\";{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=96}} Reynolds that in a digital version \"the capital letters are slightly too dark, and slightly too close to the lowercase letters that follow them in a word\"<ref name=\"Review: Graphic Design and the Soul\" /> and Wolfgang Homola that in Helvetica \"the weight of the stems of the capitals and the lower case is better balanced\".{{sfn|Homola|2004|p=33}}\n\n==Distinctive characteristics==\n[[File:Akzidenz-Grotesk comparison.png|thumb|The letterforms of Akzidenz-Grotesk show a \"folded-up\" structure with narrow [[Counter (typography)|apertures]], similar to [[Didone (typography)|Didone]] serif typefaces popular in Europe at the time, such as the work of [[Justus-Erich Walbaum]].{{efn|This image shows a later revival of Walbaum's work; during the early nineteenth century figures in roman type were customarily [[Text figures|of variable height]].}} [[Frutiger (typeface)|Frutiger]], a design intended for maximum legibility, shows a much more open design.{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=250}} Twentieth-century neo-grotesques such as Helvetica intensify the effect by making almost all terminals horizontal or vertical.<ref name=\"Gerstner English\" /><ref name=\"Gerstner German\" />]]\nCharacteristics of this typeface are:\n\n'''lower case:'''\nA 'folded-up' structure with narrow [[Counter (typography)|apertures]] and strokes curled up towards the vertical, most obvious on letters such as c, e, s and a. Stroke endings are though less consistently horizontal or vertical than in Helvetica. A square dot over the letter i. Double-storey a, single-storey g.\n\n'''upper case:'''\nG with a vertical spur. A dropped horizontal stroke on A. The capitals are wide and have relatively little variation in width, with letters like 'E' and 'F' quite wide.<ref name=\"A Neo-Grotesque Heritage\">{{cite web|last1=Berry|first1=John|title=A Neo-Grotesque Heritage|url=http://acumin.typekit.com/history/|publisher=Adobe Systems|quote=With its horizontal and vertical strokes of almost the same thickness and its regularized capital letters with few variations of width, Akzidenz Grotesk stood out starkly on the page \u2013 especially when that page also included the highly-decorated types that were popular in the same era.|accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=18}} The 'M' is straight-sided with the diagonals meeting in the bottom centre of the letter. Capitals in several weights have very noticeably thicker strokes than the lower-case.{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=61}}<ref name=\"Review: Graphic Design and the Soul\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Review: Graphic Design and the Soul |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2010/11/graphic-design-and-the-soul/ |website=TypeOff |accessdate=17 April 2019 |quote=The capital letters are slightly too dark, and slightly too close to the lowercase letters that follow them in a word.}}</ref> On many but not all styles a straight leg on the 'R' and a 'Q' where the outstroke does not cut through the letter.\n\n'''number:'''\nA top serif on the 1 and in some styles a downward-pointing serif on the top left of the 7.\n\nIt is important to note, however, that as the weights and sizes of Akzidenz-Grotesk were cut separately not all these features will appear on all styles.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /> For instance, the 't' of the Schmalhalbfett weight only has no base, as it was designed separately and not by Berthold.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" />\n\nAkzidenz-Grotesk did not have italics until the post-war period.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> Its slanted form is an [[oblique type|oblique]] rather than a [[italic type|true italic]].<ref name=Majoor>{{cite web|last1=Majoor|first1=Martin|author-link1=Martin Majoor|title=Inclined to be dull|url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature/article/inclined-to-be-dull|website=Eye magazine|accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref> This means that the letters are slanted without using handwriting forms.<ref name=\"Majoor My Type Design Philosophy\" /> During the metal type period, when italics for Akzidenz-Grotesk were not available, Amsterdam Continental marketed those of an unrelated typeface, Mercator, as companions instead.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n==Versions==\n===Metal type versions===\n[[File:Standard (Akzidenz Grotesque) Specimen (4083757282).jpg|thumb|Popular for poster setting, Akzidenz-Grotesk's bold weight has always been one of the best-known members of the family.]]\nBerthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk family by the late metal type period included the following styles. English names are taken from Berthold Schriftprobe (type specimen) No. 473 except where stated otherwise:\n* Akzidenz-Grotesk (Standard, available on Linotype in modified form as series 57 with [[Oblique type|oblique]])<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Helvetica Forever\" />{{efn|An alternative 'R' with curled leg was available by request.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}\n* Halbfett (Medium or literally semi-bold, available on Linotype in modified form as series 58 and as poster type)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Helvetica Forever\" />{{efn|An alternative 'R' with curled leg was available by request.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}\n* Mager (Light, sometimes sold as Royal-Grotesk)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Fett (Bold, available as poster type)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Schmalmager (Light Condensed)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Eng (Condensed)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Schmalhalbfett (Medium Condensed,<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> originally called \"Steinschrift eng\".{{efn|Or Enge Steinschrift}} Not designed by Berthold.<ref name=\"Reynolds typefaces named Royal or Akzidenz\" /><ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\" /> The 'R' has a curled leg and in metal type the 't' no base.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />)\n[[File:Standard Bold Condensed Type Specimen (14411557573).jpg|thumb|Akzidenz-Grotesk had several condensed weights in the metal type period, such as this condensed bold.]]\n* Schmalfett (Bold Condensed,<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /><ref name=\"Reynolds typefaces named Royal or Akzidenz\">{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=German, Swiss, and Austrian typefaces named Royal or Akzidenz |url=http://www.typeoff.de/2019/02/typefaces-with-royal-accidenz-or-akzidenz-in-their-names/ |website=TypeOff |accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"AG Re-release dates typophile\" /> originally called \"B\u00fccher-Grotesk halbfett\".{{efn|Or Halbfette B\u00fccher-Grotesk}} Available as poster type, 'R' with a curled leg)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Extra (Extrabold Condensed, tighter-spaced than the Schmalfett weight)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />\n* Extrafett (Compact, or literally, also extra-bold)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />{{efn|Ulrich Stiehl suggests that this may have been one of the last additions to the metal type family: it does not appear in a 1959 advert<ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" /> or Berthold's Hauptprobe Nr. 470, but it does in the slightly later Schriftprobe Nr. 473, which he suggests dates from c. 1966.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}\n[[File:Standard (Akzidenz Grotesque) Specimen (4083751496).jpg|thumb|With its four-terminal 'w', Akzidenz-Grotesk Skelett (Extralight Extended) was one of the most divergent and least popular members of the family in the metal type period.<ref name=\"Sowersby S\u00f6hne design information\" />]]\n* Skelett (Extralight Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Breitmager (Light Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" /><ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Breit (Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />\n* Breithalbfett (Medium Extended, or literally Semi-bold Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />{{efn|A less folded-up 'a' and 'g' and a narrower 'r' were available by request.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}<ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\n* Breitfett (Extrabold Extended, or literally Bold Extended)<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />{{efn|A less folded-up 'a' and 'g' and a narrower 'r' were available by request.<ref name=\"Schriftprobe Nr. 473\" />}}<ref name=\"Hand- und Maschinensatz (advert)\" />\nReynolds prefers 'Bold Condensed' to describe the Schmalhalbfett and 'Condensed Heavy' for the Schmalfett.<ref name=\"Klim New details\" /> Other weights were added by the time of the phototypesetting and digital versions, such as the ultra-bold 'Akzidenz-Grotesk Super'.<ref name=\"Jong Sans Serif\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n===Akzidenz-Grotesk Buch===\n[[Image:Akzidenz-Grotesk Book.svg|thumb|]]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk Buch (Book) is a variant designed by [[G\u00fcnter Gerhard Lange]] between 1969 and 1973. Designed after Helvetica had become popular, it incorporates some of its features, such as strike-through tail in 'Q', a curved tail for the 'R', horizontal and vertical cut stroke terminators.<ref name=\"Karow2012\">{{cite book|author=Peter Karow|title=Font Technology: Methods and Tools|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5MeoCAAAQBAJ|date=6 December 2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-642-78505-4|pages=225-8, 235-40}}</ref> As in some Helvetica versions, the [[cedilla]] is replaced with a comma.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schwartz|first1=Christian|title=Neue Haas Grotesk|url=http://www.christianschwartz.com/haasgrotesk.shtml|accessdate=28 November 2014}}</ref> [[Erik Spiekermann]] has described it as Lange's \"answer to Helvetica.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Spiekermann|first1=Eric|authorlink1=Erik Spiekermann|title=Twitter post|url=https://twitter.com/espiekermann/status/580497573800255488|website=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=21 July 2016|quote=AG Buch war [[Gunter Gerhard Lange|GGL's]] Antwort auf Helvetica, f\u00fcr die Berthold keine Lizenz kriegte von Linotype.}}</ref> Late in life Lange made no apology for it, commenting when asked about a design alleged to be a copy of one of his own original designs: \"there are also people who say that the best Helvetica is my AG Book.\"{{sfn|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=23}}\n\nDigital versions included Greek and Cyrillic characters, and the family includes a condensed, extended, rounded and stencil series.<ref name=\"AG Book Pro\">{{cite web|title=AG Book Pro|url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book/proplus/|publisher=Berthold|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"AG Book Rounded Pro website\">{{cite web|title=AG Book Rounded Pro|url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book-rounded/proplus/|publisher=Berthold|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n===Akzidenz-Grotesk Schulbuch===\n[[File:Akzidenz Grotesk Schulbuch.png|thumb|Akzidenz-Grotesk Schulbuch, showing its unusual capital 'i']]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk Schulbuch (Schoolbook) is a variant of Akzidenz-Grotesk Buch designed by G\u00fcnter Gerhard Lange and released in 1983.<ref name=\"Schoolbook Pro\">{{cite web |title=AG Schoolbook\u00ae Pro |url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-schoolbook/pro/ |publisher=Berthold Types |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> It uses [[schoolbook characters]], characters intended to be more distinct and closer to handwritten forms to be easier for children to recognise.<ref name=\"Walter Reynolds 2003\">{{cite journal |last1=Walker |first1=Sue |last2=Reynolds |first2=Linda |title=Serifs, sans serifs and infant characters in children\u2019s reading books |journal=Information Design Journal |date=1 January 2003 |volume=11 |issue=3 |pages=106\u2013122 |doi=10.1075/idj.11.2.04wal}}</ref>\n\nGenerally based on Akzidenz-Grotesk Book, it includes a single-storey 'a', curled 'l', lower- and upper-case 'k' that are symmetrical, and 't', 'u' and 'y' without curls on the base. The 'J' has a top bar, the 'M' centre does not descend to the baseline and the 'G' and 'R' are simplified in the manner of [[Futura (typeface)|Futura]]. A particularly striking feature is a blackletter-style default upper-case 'i' with a curl at the bottom: this is rarely encountered in the English-speaking world (it would more commonly be recognized as a J), but much more common in Germany.<ref name=\"Wikipedia Redefined\">{{cite web|last1=Coles|first1=Stephen|title=Wikipedia Redefined|url=http://fontsinuse.com/uses/2013/wikipedia-redefined|website=Fonts in Use|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Design Museum FIU\">{{cite web|last1=Coles|first1=Stephen|title=Design Museum|url=http://fontsinuse.com/uses/11997/design-museum-identity-2003-2016|website=Fonts in Use|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nEach weight is available in two fonts featuring alternative designs. In 2008, OpenType Pro versions of the fonts were released. [[FontFont]]'s FF Schulbuch family is in a similar style.<ref name=\"Design Museum FIU\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n===Akzidenz-Grotesk Old Face===\n[[File:Akzidenz Grotesk Old Face.png|thumb|Sample image of Akzidenz-Grotesk Old Face, a [[phototypesetting]] version of Akzidenz-Grotesk intended to incorporate more of the original inconsistencies and different x-heights of the metal type]]\nAkzidenz-Grotesk Old Face, designed by [[G\u00fcnter Gerhard Lange]] and released in 1984, was intended to be more true to the metal type than previous phototypesetting versions and incorporate more of the original type's inconsistencies of dimensions such as x-height.<ref name=\"AG Old Face Pro website\">{{cite web|title=AG Old Face Pro|url=https://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-old-face/pro/|publisher=Berthold Types|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Schwemer-Scheddin|2003|p=26}} It also incorporates a comma-style cedilla in the medium and bold weights, inward hook in regular-weighted [[\u00df]], and a shortened horizontal serif on the regular-weighted ''1''.<ref name=\"AG Old Face weights\" />\n\nRegular, medium, bold, outline, bold outline and shaded styles were made for the family, but no obliques.<ref name=\"AG Old Face weights\">{{cite book|title=Berthold exklusiv Probe 013: Akzidenz-Grotesk|date=1984|publisher=Berthold Fototype|location=Berlin|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/101656904@N05/33820314480/in/album-72157679746685343/|accessdate=1 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"AG Old Face Pro website\" />\n\n===Akzidenz-Grotesk Next===\nIn December 2006, Berthold announced the release of Akzidenz-Grotesk Next.<ref>[http://www.microsoft.com/typography/links/news.aspx?NID=5711 Berthold Releases Akzidenz-Grotesk Next]</ref> Designed by Bernd M\u00f6llenst\u00e4dt and Dieter Hofrichter, this typeface family features readjusted x-heights and weights throughout the family, giving a more consistent design. The family consists of 14 variants with 7 weights in roman and italic, in a single width.\n{{clear}}\n==Similarities to other typefaces==\n[[Image:AGcomparison08.svg|thumb|Comparison of distinguishing characters in Akzidenz-Grotesk, [[Folio (typeface)|Folio]], [[Helvetica]], and [[Univers|Univers 55]]]]\n[[Image:Akzindenz-helvetica-xheight.svg|thumb|The regular weight of Akzidenz-Grotesk had a lower x-height than [[Helvetica]]]]\nSeveral type designers modelled typefaces on this popular typeface in the 1950s; Reynolds comments that the original Akzidenz-Grotesk has limitations in extended text: \"the capital letters are slightly too dark.\"<ref name=\"Review: Graphic Design and the Soul\" /> [[Max Miedinger]] at the Haas Foundry used it as a model for the typeface Neue Haas-Grotesk, released in 1957 and renamed Helvetica in 1961. Miedinger sought to refine the typeface making it more even and unified, with a higher x-height, tighter spacing and generally horizontal terminals.<ref name=\"The Birth of a Giant\" /> Two other releases from 1957, Adrian Frutiger's Univers and Bauer's Folio, take inspiration from Akzidenz-Grotesk; Frutiger's goal was to eliminate what he saw as unnecessary details, removing the dropped spur at bottom right of the G and converting the '1' and the '7' into two straight lines.<ref name=\"Gehlhaar\">{{cite web |last1=Gehlhaar |first1=Jens |title=Neuwelt: an optimistic transatlantic sans serif type family |url=https://jensgehlhaar.com/Neuwelt-An-optimistic-transatlantic-sans-serif-type-family |website=Jens Gehlhaar |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>{{sfn|Frutiger|2009|p=97|ps=: \"The curved indent in the upstroke of the 1, like in Akzidenz Grotesk, was something alien to me. An upstroke is something simple and not so fanciful, horizontal with a bump in it. Accordingly, my 1 is simple, like the 7 is too.\"}}\n\nMuch more loosely, [[Transport (typeface)|Transport]], the typeface used on British road signs, was designed by [[Jock Kinneir]] and [[Margaret Calvert]] influenced by Akzidenz-Grotesk.<ref name=\"New Transport\">{{cite web|title=New Transport|first=Margaret|last=Calvert|author-link=Margaret Calvert|url=http://www.newtransport.co.uk/|publisher=A2-Type|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> However, many adaptations and letters influenced by other typefaces were incorporated to increase legibility and make characters more distinct.<ref name=\"From Akzidenz to Transport Solution\">{{cite web|last1=Sudjic|first1=Deyan|title=From Akzidenz to Transport Solution|url=http://www.port-magazine.com/design/from-akzidenz-to-transport-solution/|website=Port|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Jackson2013\">{{cite book|first=Tanya|last=Jackson|title=British Railways: The Nation's Railway|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jcc7AwAAQBAJ&pg=PT130|date=31 January 2013|publisher=History Press|isbn=978-0-7524-9742-6|page=130}}</ref>\n\n===\"Akzidenz-Grotesk\" (Haas)===\n{{main|Normal-Grotesk}}\nA completely different \"Akzidenz-Grotesk\" was made by the [[Haas Type Foundry]] of Switzerland. Also named \"Accidenz-Grotesk\" and \"Normal-Grotesk\", it had a more condensed, \"boxy\" design.<ref name=\"Eskilson2012\">{{cite book|first=Stephen|last=Eskilson|title=Graphic Design: A New History, Second Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WUEv45FsrmsC&pg=PA290|date=28 February 2012|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-17260-7|pages=290\u20131}}</ref><ref name=\"The Birth of a Giant\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=The Birth of a Giant|url=http://www.fontbureau.com/nhg/history/|publisher=[[Font Bureau]]|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref> Kupferschmid describes it as a \"reworking of \"Neue Moderne Grotesk\", originally ca. 1909 by Wagner & Schmidt, Leipzig. Initially issued by Haas under the name \"Accidenz-Grotesk\", later spelled \"Akzidenz-Grotesk\" but 1943 revised and renamed \"Normal-Grotesk\" to prevent confusion with Berthold's Akzidenz-Grotesk.\"<ref name=\"Haas Normal-Grotesk Flickr\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=Haas Normal-Grotesk|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/kupfers/6198185700|website=Flickr|accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Wagner & Schmidt, etc.\">{{cite web|last1=Kupferschmid|first1=Indra|title=Wagner & Schmidt, etc.|url=http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2016/10/wagner-schmidt-etc/|website=kupferschrift|accessdate=18 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119053731/http://kupferschrift.de/cms/2016/10/wagner-schmidt-etc/|archive-date=19 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Haas Foundry created [[Helvetica]] (then called \"Neue Haas Grotesk\") due to its decline in popularity in competition with Berthold's design.<ref name=\"Eskilson2012\"/>\n\n===Alternative digitisations===\nAs typeface designs are generally not legally protected (unlike their names, which can be trademarked),<ref name=\"AG Next Trademark\">{{cite web |title=AKZIDENZ-GROTESK NEXT \u2013 Trademark Details |url=https://trademarks.justia.com/872/09/akzidenz-grotesk-87209238.html |publisher=Just |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> several alternative digitisations inspired by Akzidenz-Grotesk have been released under alternative names. The Swiss digital type foundry Optimo has released an alternative digitisation of Akzidenz-Grotesk named \"Theinhardt\".<ref name=\"Theinhardt Grotesk\">{{cite web|title=Theinhardt|url=http://optimo.ch/typefaces_Theinhardt_all_Specimen.html|publisher=Optimo|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> [[Erik Spiekermann]] has praised this as \"the best\" Akzidenz-Grotesk digitisation.<ref name=\"Thienhardt Spiekermann\">{{cite web|last1=Spiekermann|first1=Erik|authorlink1=Erik Spiekermann|title=Twitter post|url=https://twitter.com/espiekermann/status/580502828122284032|website=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=21 July 2016|quote=ist ja auch die beste AG}}</ref> [[Mergenthaler Linotype Company|Linotype]], which started to sell Akzidenz-Grotesk on its hot metal typesetting system in the 1950s, continues to sell a limited digital version under the other common alternative name, 'Basic Commercial', and [[Bitstream Inc.|Bitstream]] offer a two-weight version named 'Gothic 725'.<ref name=\"Basic Commercial LT\">{{cite web|title=Basic Commercial LT|url=https://www.myfonts.com/fonts/linotype/basic-commercial-lt/|website=MyFonts|publisher=Linotype|accessdate=20 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Gothic 725\">{{cite web|title=Gothic 725|url=https://www.myfonts.com/fonts/bitstream/gothic-725/|website=[[MyFonts]]|publisher=[[Bitstream Inc.]]|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> A proprietary digitisation named NYC Sans, by Nick Sherman and Jeremy Mickel, is the corporate font of New York City's tourist board [[NYC & Company]].<ref name=\"NYC Sans Hex\">{{cite web |title=NYC Sans |url=https://hex.xyz |publisher=Hex Projects |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NYC SANS - Trademark Details\">{{cite web |title=NYC SANS \u2013 Trademark Details |url=https://trademarks.justia.com/865/03/nyc-86503390.html |publisher=[[Justia]] |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NYC Gets A Major Rebrand FastCo\">{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Meg |title=NYC Gets A Major Rebrand (And Its First Official Pictograms) |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3060794/nyc-gets-a-major-rebrand-and-its-first-official-pictograms |website=Fast Company |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Lessard NYC Go rebrand details\">{{cite web |last1=Lessard |first1=Emily |title=NYC Go rebrand details |url=http://emilylessard.com/nycgo-typography/ |publisher=Emily Lessard |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> Transport has also been digitised in several versions.<ref name=\"Transport URW\">{{cite web|title=Transport|url=http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/urw/transport/|website=MyFonts|publisher=URW++|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"New Transport\" /> The American publisher CastleType has released a digitisation originally created for ''[[San Francisco Focus]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"Standard CT\">{{cite web |last1=Castle |first1=Jason |title=Standard CT |url=https://www.myfonts.com/fonts/castletype/standard/ |website=[[MyFonts]] |publisher=CastleType |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> Spiekermann has also released with Ralph du Carrois a very loose digitisation of Akzidenz Grotesk, FF Real, in two [[optical size]]s, with variant features like a two-storey 'g', [[Typographic ligature|ligatures]], and a true italic.<ref name=\"FF Real LT\">{{cite web|title=FF Real|url=https://www.linotype.com/8050/ff-real.html|website=Linotype|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Interview with Erik Spiekermann and Ralph du Carrois\">{{cite web|last=Ulrich|first=Ferdinand|title=Interview with Erik Spiekermann and Ralph du Carrois|url=https://www.fontshop.com/content/interview-with-erik-spiekermann-and-ralph-olivier-du-carrois-1|website=FontShop|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> A digitisation named S\u00f6hne, in three widths with [[Monospaced typeface|a monospaced version]] was released by Kris Sowersby in 2019.<ref name=\"Sowersby S\u00f6hne design information\">{{cite web |last1=Sowersby |first1=Kris |title=S\u00f6hne design information |url=https://klim.co.nz/blog/soehne-design-information/ |publisher=[[Klim Type Foundry]] |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Klim New details\" /><ref name=\"Stinson S\u00f6hne\">{{cite web |last1=Stinson |first1=Liz |title=A Modern Sans-serif Infused With the Spirit of the NYC Subway |url=https://eyeondesign.aiga.org/a-modern-sans-serif-infused-with-the-spirit-of-the-nyc-subway/ |website=AIGA Eye On Design |publisher=[[AIGA]] |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> A digitisation of Stefan George-Schrift by Colin Kahn has been published by [[P22 (type foundry)|P22]].<ref name=\"P22 St G Schrift\">{{cite web |title=St G Schrift |url=https://p22.com/family-St_G_Schrift |publisher=[[P22 (type foundry)|P22]] |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notable users==\n<!-- **ALL** uses need a reference -->\n[[File:Gestaltungsprobleme cover comparison.jpg|thumb|The cover of Josef M\u00fcller-Brockmann's 1961 book ''The Graphic Artist and His Design Problems'' used Akzidenz-Grotesk. It was replaced with Helvetica in later editions.]]\n[[File:KAS-Berlin-Wilmersdorf-Bild-13303-1.jpg|thumb|Political debate, [[West Berlin]], 1970]]\nBesides uses in Swiss-style poster design, Akzidenz-Grotesk and Georgia are the official fonts of the [[American Red Cross]].<ref name=\"http://www.rockriver.redcross.org/media/Brand_Standards.pdf\">[http://www.rockriver.redcross.org/media/Brand_Standards.pdf American Red Cross Brand Standards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812094946/http://www.rockriver.redcross.org/media/Brand_Standards.pdf |date=2010-08-12 }}</ref> Akzidenz-Grotesk is also the font used in [[Arizona State University]]'s brand logo.<ref name=\"https://commguide.asu.edu/downloads/fonts\">[https://commguide.asu.edu/downloads/fonts Arizona State University Communication Guide | Font Standard]</ref>\n\nBerthold sued [[Target Corporation]] for copyright infringement and breach of contract in 2017, alleging that Target had asked a design firm to use the font in a promotional video without a license.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/commercialcontracts/articles/971652/chicago-font-co-takes-aim-at-target-s-use-of-typeface/|title=Chicago Font Co. Takes Aim at Target's Use Of Typeface \u2013 Law360|website=www.law360.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-06}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Berthold typesetting systems#Berthold ADS (Akzidenz Dialog System)|Berthold Akzidenz Dialog System]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Frutiger|first1=Adrian|authorlink1=Adrian Frutiger|editor1-last=Osterer|editor1-first=Heiden|editor2-last=Stamm|editor2-first=Philipp|title=Typefaces: The Complete Works|date=2009|publisher=Birkh\u00e4user|location=Basel|isbn=978-3764385811|edition=English}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Gerstner|first1=Karl|authorlink1=Karl Gerstner|title=Die alte Akzidenz-Grotesk auf neuer Basis|journal=Der Druckspiegel|date=1963|url=http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/akzidenz-grotesk-auf-neuer-basis-german-original.pdf|accessdate=15 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015202204/http://forgotten-shapes.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/akzidenz-grotesk-auf-neuer-basis-german-original.pdf|archive-date=2017-10-15|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hollis|first=Richard|title=Swiss Graphic Design: The Origins and Growth of an International Style, 1920\u20131965|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7XO-LMDo4yQC&pg=PA201|year=2006|publisher=Laurence King Publishing|isbn=978-1-85669-487-2}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Homola|first1=Wolfgang|title=Type design in the age of the machine. The \u2018Breite Grotesk\u2019 by J. G. Schelter & Giesecke|url=http://www.typefacedesign.org/resources/dissertation/2004/WolfgangHomola_dissertation.pdf|date=2004|publisher=University of Reading (archived)|accessdate=17 January 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112014111/http://www.typefacedesign.org/resources/dissertation/2004/WolfgangHomola_dissertation.pdf|archivedate=12 January 2011}}\n* {{cite book |last1=M\u00fcller|first1=Lars|last2=Malsy|first2=Victor|last3=Kupferschmid|first3=Indra|title=Helvetica Forever: Story of a Typeface|date=2009|publisher=Lars M\u00fcller|isbn=978-3037781210}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=The godfather: retracing the origins of Akzidenz-Grotesk |journal=Footnotes |date=2019 |issue=3 |}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Schriftk\u00fcnstler \u2013 A historiographic examination of the relationship between handcraft and art regarding the design and making of printers\u2019 type in Germany between 1871 and 1914 |date=2020 |publisher=Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Braunschweig (PhD thesis) |url=https://www.academia.edu/42108215/Chapter_1_Schriftku_nstler_A_historiographic_examination_of_the_relationship_between_handcraft_and_art_regarding_the_design_and_making_of_printers_type_in_Germany_between_1871_and_1914 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |chapter=Chapter 1}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Reynolds |first1=Dan |title=Schriftk\u00fcnstler \u2013 A historiographic examination of the relationship between handcraft and art regarding the design and making of printers\u2019 type in Germany between 18