racy|title=Letters of Credit: A View of Type Design|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8NssjbqNcsC&pg=PA194|date=2003|publisher=D.R. Godine|isbn=978-1-56792-240-0}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*Berthold pages: [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book/proplus/ AG Book Pro+], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book-rounded/proplus/ AG Book Rounded], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-book-stencil-et-al/pro/ AG Book Stencil et al], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-old-face/pro/ AG Old Face], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/ag-schoolbook/pro/ AG Schoolbook], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/akzidenz-grotesk/proplus/ Akzidenz-Grotesk Pro+], [http://www.bertholdtypes.com/font/akzidenz-grotesk-next-family/pro/ Akzidenz-Grotesk Next]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110719030422/http://www.sanskritweb.net/fontdocs/#Akzidenz Akzidenz Grotesk sample books] digitised by Ulrich Stiehl\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/n1ke/albums/72157629429950223 Berthold specimens from c. 1913], showing Schattierte-Grotesk and co-branding mentioning Berthold and Bauer\n* ''Fonts in Use'' coverage: [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/76/akzidenz-grotesk Akzidenz-Grotesk], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/31705/akzidenz-grotesk-condensed AG Condensed], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/7248/ag-book AG Book], [https://fontsinuse.com/typefaces/574/standard Standard] (for American uses)\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/stewf/sets/72157661987768480 Probe 429A] (c. 1960 specimen, photographed by Stephen Coles/Thomas Maier)\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/101656904@N05/sets/72157679746685343 Berthold exklusiv 013: Akzidenz-Grotesk] (1980s Berthold specimen, for phototypesetting)\n* [http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GG/1937-08-01/edition/null/page/5 Berthold advertisement from 1937] not showing Akzidenz-Grotesk. The advert showcases \"modern and successful\" faces, illustrating the eclipse of Akzidenz-Grotesk in this period.\n* [http://magazines.iaddb.org/issue/GG/1959-01-01/edition/null/page/68 1959 advert] announcing the arrival of Akzidenz-Grotesk on the Linotype hot metal system\n\n[[Category:Berthold typefaces]]\n[[Category:Grotesque sans-serif typefaces]]\n[[Category:Letterpress typefaces]]\n[[Category:Photocomposition typefaces]]\n[[Category:Typefaces with infant variants]]\n[[Category:Digital typefaces]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1898]]\n[[Category:Linotype typefaces]]\n", "name_user": "Blythwood", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copyedit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akzidenz-Grotesk"}
{"title_page": "Charles W. Brouse", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Charles W. Brouse\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1839|12|30}}\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1904|10|26|1839|12|30}}\n|placeofburial=[[Crown Hill National Cemetery]], [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n|placeofburial_label=Place of burial\n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|birth_place=[[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n|death_place= \n|allegiance={{flagicon|United States|1861}} [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch={{army|USA}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|rank=[[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|serviceyears=1862 - 1865\n|unit={{flagicon|Indiana}} [[100th Regiment Indiana Volunteer Infantry]]\n|battles=[[Battle of Missionary Ridge]]\n|awards={{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n'''Charles W. Brouse''' (December 30, 1839 &ndash; October 26, 1904) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who received the [[Medal of Honor]] for valor during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Biography==\nBrouse was commissioned as a Captain of the [[100th Indiana Infantry Regiment]] in August 1862, and was discharged due to disability in January 1865. <ref>[http://www.indianadigitalarchives.org/ViewRecord.aspx?RID=291A0540D84B928B5F308A57377ECBBC Indiana Digital Archives]</ref> He received the Medal of Honor on May 16, 1899, for his actions at the [[Battle of Missionary Ridge]].\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n'''Citation:'''\n\n<blockquote> To encourage his men whom he had ordered to lie down while under severe fire, and who were partially protected by slight earthworks, himself refused to lie down, but walked along the top of the works until he fell severely wounded. <ref>[http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/158/brouse-charles-w.php Congressional Medal of Honor Society]</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A-F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20130729133545/http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=470 Military Times]\n*{{Find a Grave|6274701}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brouse, Charles W.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1904 deaths]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:People of Indiana in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Charles W. Brouse\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1839|12|30}}\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1904|10|26|1839|12|30}}\n|placeofburial=[[Crown Hill National Cemetery]], [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n|placeofburial_label=Place of burial\n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|birth_place=[[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n|death_place= \n|allegiance={{flagicon|United States|1861}} [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch={{army|USA}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|rank=[[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|serviceyears=1862 - 1865\n|unit={{flagicon|Indiana}} [[100th Indiana Infantry Regiment]]\n|battles=[[Battle of Missionary Ridge]]\n|awards={{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n'''Charles W. Brouse''' (December 30, 1839 &ndash; October 26, 1904) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who received the [[Medal of Honor]] for valor during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Biography==\nBrouse was commissioned as a Captain of the [[100th Indiana Infantry Regiment]] in August 1862, and was discharged due to disability in January 1865. <ref>[http://www.indianadigitalarchives.org/ViewRecord.aspx?RID=291A0540D84B928B5F308A57377ECBBC Indiana Digital Archives]</ref> He received the Medal of Honor on May 16, 1899, for his actions at the [[Battle of Missionary Ridge]].\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n'''Citation:'''\n\n<blockquote> To encourage his men whom he had ordered to lie down while under severe fire, and who were partially protected by slight earthworks, himself refused to lie down, but walked along the top of the works until he fell severely wounded. <ref>[http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/158/brouse-charles-w.php Congressional Medal of Honor Society]</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A-F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20130729133545/http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=470 Military Times]\n*{{Find a Grave|6274701}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brouse, Charles W.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1904 deaths]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:People of Indiana in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_W._Brouse"}
